{"type":"text","timestamp":1778725759096,"sessionID":"ses_1dbb77ea5ffelbBmi4JoXOq6eL","part":{"id":"prt_e24510c9a0018z0nAKq4q1reE7","messageID":"msg_e2450f970001n9QsKXQVfCQEHl","sessionID":"ses_1dbb77ea5ffelbBmi4JoXOq6eL","type":"text","text":"**Hypothesis written** to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r2s0.yaml`.\n\n### Summary\n\n**Angle:** MEM-stage load-result forwarding to eliminate the classic 1-cycle load-use stall.\n\n**What it changes:**\n- Exposes the MEM-stage combinational `load_data` (already computed from `dmem_rdata`) as a new forwarding source.\n- Extends `forward_unit`/`ex_stage` to select this source when the instruction in MEM is a LOAD and its `rd` matches the EX-stage `rs1`/`rs2`.\n- Removes the `load_use_hazard` stall logic from `hazard_unit` entirely, since the bypass now covers the dependency.\n\n**Why it should help:**\n- CoreMark spends a measurable fraction of cycles stalled on load→ALU and load→store dependencies.\n- This saves **one bubble per load-use** without adding pipeline stages, branch predictors, or multi-cycle units.\n- The forwarding path is short (`dmem_rdata` → byte-align mux → EX operand mux → ALU) and should have negligible Fmax impact because the FPGA BRAM output is typically registered.\n\n**Expected fitness delta:** +5 % (medium confidence).","time":{"start":1778725751962,"end":1778725759089}}}
