{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778727230810,"sessionID":"ses_1dba172feffe2KO65sK7StgYiJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r3s2.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r3s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\n2: title: 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\n6:   but every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\n7:   not-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\n8:   function calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\n9:   addresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\n10:   improving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\n13:   return-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\n14:   RAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\n15:   In the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\n16:   onto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\n17:   !flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\n18:   redirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\n19: expected_impact:\n20:   fitness_delta_pct: 5\n21:   confidence: medium\n22: changes:\n23:   - file: rtl/ras.sv\n24:     description: New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\n25:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n26:     description: Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\n27:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n28:     description: Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\n29:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n30:     description: Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\n\n(End of file - total 30 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\ntitle: 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\n  but every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\n  not-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\n  function calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\n  addresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\n  improving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\n  return-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\n  RAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\n  In the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\n  onto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\n  !flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\n  redirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r3s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778727230797,"end":1778727230809}},"id":"prt_e246798f2001LBHB7Pn2MXL4Ez","sessionID":"ses_1dba172feffe2KO65sK7StgYiJ","messageID":"msg_e246786fd001kxbjDg5tobVNNO"}}
