{"type":"text","timestamp":1778725875137,"sessionID":"ses_1dbb77f04ffeUuJAi3ZE1gN2lx","part":{"id":"prt_e2452d446001py944S0K7KeOwb","messageID":"msg_e2452b854001sMV72175uT2tQS","sessionID":"ses_1dbb77f04ffeUuJAi3ZE1gN2lx","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the structural hypothesis to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n\nAdd a **MEM-to-EX combinational forwarding path** for loaded data so that dependent ALU, load, and store instructions can execute in the cycle immediately after a load enters MEM, eliminating the 1-cycle load-use stall for the common case. To avoid correctness issues where a branch/JALR might compute an incorrect redirect from invalid data during a `dmem_ready=0` stall, the load-use stall is **retained only for control-flow instructions** (branches and JALR). This is a classic structural bypass that directly improves IPC on CoreMark's memory-heavy kernels without touching the critical Fmax path.","time":{"start":1778725868614,"end":1778725875137}}}
