{"type":"text","timestamp":1778726854598,"sessionID":"ses_1dba1735effe7w9m8bQXcNkDCR","part":{"id":"prt_e2461c2a40017Ep4YSVmGxqgaW","messageID":"msg_e2461b3e2001UwWLTtQpld00hE","sessionID":"ses_1dba1735effe7w9m8bQXcNkDCR","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis file:\n\n**`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r3s2.yaml`**\n\n**Proposed change:** Add a **4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS)** to predict `JALR` function returns. The existing static predictor already catches backward branches and `JAL`, but every `ret` (`JALR x0, x1, 0`) is currently mispredicted, costing a 2-cycle flush. CoreMark is call-heavy, so eliminating these mispredicts should improve IPC with only ~128 FFs and negligible Fmax risk.\n\n**Key points:**\n- **IF stage:** Detect return-pattern `JALR` (rd=x0, rs1=x1); predict taken to RAS top when stack is non-empty.\n- **ID stage:** Push `PC+4` on calls (`JAL`/`JALR` writing x1); pop on returns. Updates are gated by `!flush` so wrong-path instructions cannot corrupt the stack.\n- **EX stage:** Continues to verify predictions and redirect on mispredict — no changes to the redirect logic itself.\n- **Area/Fmax:** Very small (4×32-bit stack + 2-bit pointer), read path is just a register mux, unlikely to create a new critical path.","time":{"start":1778726847140,"end":1778726854596}}}
