a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 4.5, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:01:44.327280Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (improvement, +4.50%): Function returns (JALR rd=x0, rs1=x1) dominate mispredicts in call-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark; a tiny 4-entry RAS correctly predicts them with minimal area and no impact on EX/MEM timing, yielding pure IPC upside.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/bimodal_pred.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\\nalgorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\\nstage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\\ndecodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\\ndiv_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\\nsimplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\\nremoves the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\\nsignificantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"implementation_compile_failed: \", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Instantiating a new `div_unit` submodule without creating its `.sv` source file or adding it to the build manifest causes immediate compile failure; new RTL modules must be created and included before integration.\\n\\n(End of file - total 5 lines)\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry bimodal predictor for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\\nwith PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\\noffset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\\nthe existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\\nstage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\\nincrement if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\\nall counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\\ncurrent static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\\nto the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect\\nthe fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:35:25.447373Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r5s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r5s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r5s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 5}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with inlined iterative multi-cycle FSM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from alu.sv (keep the\\nALTOPS formal branch unchanged). Implement a 32-cycle shift-subtract\\ndivider as a local always_ff FSM directly inside ex_stage.sv\\u2014no new\\nmodule file is required. The FSM converts signed operands to magnitude,\\nperforms unsigned shift-subtract for 32 cycles, then restores the sign\\nfor DIV/REM. When a divide opcode is decoded in EX, ex_stage starts the\\nFSM and asserts div_busy. hazard_unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the FSM finishes. The result is\\ncaptured into the EX/MEM register on the final cycle. Because the ALU\\nmodule loses its clockless divider, the cocotb ALU unit tests for\\nDIV/REM must be removed.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases from the case\\nstatement; they now fall to default (output 32'b0). Keep the\\n`ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged so formal\\nverification continues to see combinational behaviour.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an inline 32-cycle shift-subtract divider FSM (always_ff)\\ninside ex_stage. On detecting a DIV/REM opcode, latch the operands,\\nrun 32 cycles of shift/subtract, and capture the final quotient or\\nremainder into the EX/MEM alu_result field. Assert a new div_busy\\noutput while the FSM is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update\\nwith !div_busy so the divide instruction stays in EX until done.\\nEnsure non-divide instructions continue to flow in a single cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Combine it with dmem_stall so that\\nstall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb are all asserted\\nwhile div_busy is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove or comment out all DIV/REM cocotb tests (div_signed,\\ndiv_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed,\\nrem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides)\\nbecause the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases from the case\\nstatement; they now fall to default (output 32'b0). Keep the\\n`ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged so formal\\nverification continues to see combinational behaviour.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an inline 32-cycle shift-subtract divider FSM (always_ff)\\ninside ex_stage. On detecting a DIV/REM opcode, latch the operands,\\nrun 32 cycles of shift/subtract, and capture the final quotient or\\nremainder into the EX/MEM alu_result field. Assert a new div_busy\\noutput while the FSM is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update\\nwith !div_busy so the divide instruction stays in EX until done.\\nEnsure non-divide instructions continue to flow in a single cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Combine it with dmem_stall so that\\nstall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb are all asserted\\nwhile div_busy is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove or comment out all DIV/REM cocotb tests (div_signed,\\ndiv_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed,\\nrem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides)\\nbecause the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry BTB to remove IF-stage target adder and extend branch coverage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 280.97, \"delta_pct\": -15.17, \"vs_baseline\": -0.65, \"fmax_mhz\": 118.62, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4221744, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 12328, \"ff\": 2983, \"seeds\": [118.62, 121.34, 116.46], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:27:55.029690Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r6s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r6s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r6s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r6s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with proven PicoRV32 iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from `alu.sv` (keep the\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch unchanged so formal verification still sees\\ncombinational behaviour). Adapt the `picorv32_pcpi_div` module from\\n`cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` into a new standalone `div_unit.sv` with a\\nsimplified interface: `start`, `op` (one-hot DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), `a`, `b`,\\n`result`, `busy`, `done`. Integrate the unit into the EX stage: when a divide\\nopcode is decoded, start `div_unit` and assert `div_busy`. Hold the EX/MEM\\nregister while `div_busy` is high; on `done` capture the result into\\n`reg_q.alu_result`. Extend `hazard_unit` to treat `div_busy` like\\n`dmem_stall`, freezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider finishes. Wire\\n`div_busy` through `core.sv`. The cocotb ALU unit tests for division must be\\nremoved because the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 15, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New module adapted from `cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` module `picorv32_pcpi_div`. Simplified to expose `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `result`, `busy`, `done`. Handles signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32IM. Keeps the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch from the original.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the case statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0`. Keep the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide opcodes and start `div_unit`. Assert a new `div_busy` output while the unit is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update with `!div_busy`; capture `div_unit.result` into `reg_q.alu_result` on the final cycle. Non-divide instructions continue single-cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Combine it with `dmem_stall` 