{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778747396320,"sessionID":"ses_1da682a42ffez3xzzAjo8h03Of","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"tail -n 5 cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -c \"import sys,json; [print(json.dumps(json.loads(line), indent=2)) for line in sys.stdin]\"","description":"Pretty-print last 5 log lines"},"output":"{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\",\n  \"title\": \"1-entry skid buffer in IF to decouple fetch from back-end stalls\",\n  \"category\": \"structural\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer inside `if_stage.sv` consisting of a single\\n`if_id_t` register and a valid bit.  When the downstream ID stage is stalled\\n(`stall_id` asserted) and the buffer is empty, the buffer latches the current\\nvalid fetch bundle.  When the buffer is valid it drives the stage `out` port\\ninstead of the raw combinational fetch.  The buffer is cleared on reset,\\nredirect, or `flush_if`.  Restructure `hazard_unit.sv` so that `stall_if`\\nonly asserts when `imem_ready` is low OR when the buffer is already full\\nduring a back-end stall (`load_use_hazard || dmem_stall`).  `flush_if`\\nasserts only on `redirect` or on `imem_stall` when the buffer is empty.\\nLeave `stall_id`, `flush_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` unchanged.\\nWire the new `buf_valid` status signal and the existing `stall_id` signal\\nthrough `core.sv`.  No other RTL files are modified.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 4,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 4,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 331.22,\n  \"delta_pct\": 0.0,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 17.11,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4245805,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10038,\n  \"ff\": 2028,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    125.72,\n    140.63,\n    142.37\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:46:28.944830Z\",\n  \"slot\": 1,\n  \"round_id\": 11,\n  \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r11s1 (regression, +0.00%): A 1-entry IF skid buffer cannot improve IPC when the benchmark is back-end bound by EX/MEM-stage hazards and multi-cycle dmem stalls; front-end decoupling only creates slack that the stalled back-end cannot absorb.\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\",\n  \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"outcome\": \"broken\",\n  \"formal_passed\": false,\n  \"cosim_passed\": false,\n  \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r11s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r11s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r11s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r11s2'])\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 11\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r12s0\",\n  \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\",\n  \"category\": \"micro_opt\",\n  \"outcome\": \"broken\",\n  \"formal_passed\": false,\n  \"cosim_passed\": false,\n  \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r12s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\",\n  \"slot\": 0,\n  \"round_id\": 12\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\",\n  \"title\": \"Add 1-entry pending-store slot to decouple store retirement from dmem stalls\",\n  \"category\": \"structural\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a 1-entry store_slot module between the MEM stage and the\\nexternal dmem port.  When mem_stage detects a valid, aligned store\\nto normal RAM (below 0x00100000) and the slot is empty, it retires\\nthe store into the slot and de-asserts mem_wait so the pipeline\\ncontinues.  The slot drains to the dmem port whenever dmemReady is\\nhigh.  Younger loads and non-bufferable stores wait in MEM while the\\nslot is valid, preserving load-after-store ordering.  Adapt\\nhazard_unit to stall on the precise mem_wait signal exported by\\nmem_stage instead of the coarse dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op\\ncombination.  This structural decoupling recovers cycles lost to\\nstore-related dmem stalls without touching the ALU or fetch paths.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 305.1,\n  \"delta_pct\": -7.89,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 7.88,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 128.53,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4212703,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10075,\n  \"ff\": 2033,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    126.9,\n    129.22,\n    128.53\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:19:44.287568Z\",\n  \"slot\": 1,\n  \"round_id\": 12,\n  \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\",\n  \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 1-bit BHT for forward branches\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped branch history table with 1-bit saturating\\ncounters indexed by PC[6:2]. In IF, forward conditional branches consult the\\nBHT: if the bit is 1, predict taken (target is the existing b_target);\\nbackward branches keep their existing static-taken override. In EX, when a\\nforward branch resolves, update the corresponding entry (set to branch_taken).\\nThis should shave mispredicts on biased forward branches with negligible\\narea/Fmax cost.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 324.68,\n  \"delta_pct\": -1.97,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 14.8,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 137.53,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4235852,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10802,\n  \"ff\": 2065,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    135.92,\n    137.53,\n    142.43\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_pass