e PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer inside `if_stage.sv` consisting of a single\\n`if_id_t` register and a valid bit.  When the downstream ID stage is stalled\\n(`stall_id` asserted) and the buffer is empty, the buffer latches the current\\nvalid fetch bundle.  When the buffer is valid it drives the stage `out` port\\ninstead of the raw combinational fetch.  The buffer is cleared on reset,\\nredirect, or `flush_if`.  Restructure `hazard_unit.sv` so that `stall_if`\\nonly asserts when `imem_ready` is low OR when the buffer is already full\\nduring a back-end stall (`load_use_hazard || dmem_stall`).  `flush_if`\\nasserts only on `redirect` or on `imem_stall` when the buffer is empty.\\nLeave `stall_id`, `flush_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` unchanged.\\nWire the new `buf_valid` status signal and the existing `stall_id` signal\\nthrough `core.sv`.  No other RTL files are modified.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:46:28.944830Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 11, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r11s1 (regression, +0.00%): A 1-entry IF skid buffer cannot improve IPC when the benchmark is back-end bound by EX/MEM-stage hazards and multi-cycle dmem stalls; front-end decoupling only creates slack that the stalled back-end cannot absorb.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r11s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r11s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r11s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r11s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 11}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r12s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 12}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry pending-store slot to decouple store retirement from dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a 1-entry store_slot module between the MEM stage and the\\nexternal dmem port.  When mem_stage detects a valid, aligned store\\nto normal RAM (below 0x00100000) and the slot is empty, it retires\\nthe store into the slot and de-asserts mem_wait so the pipeline\\ncontinues.  The slot drains to the dmem port whenever dmemReady is\\nhigh.  Younger loads and non-bufferable stores wait in MEM while the\\nslot is valid, preserving load-after-store ordering.  Adapt\\nhazard_unit to stall on the precise mem_wait signal exported by\\nmem_stage instead of the coarse dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op\\ncombination.  This structural decoupling recovers cycles lost to\\nstore-related dmem stalls without touching the ALU or fetch paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 305.1, \"delta_pct\": -7.89, \"vs_baseline\": 7.88, \"fmax_mhz\": 128.53, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4212703, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10075, \"ff\": 2033, \"seeds\": [126.9, 129.22, 128.53], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:19:44.287568Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 12, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 1-bit BHT for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped branch history table with 1-bit saturating\\ncounters indexed by PC[6:2]. In IF, forward conditional branches consult the\\nBHT: if the bit is 1, predict taken (target is the existing b_target);\\nbackward branches keep their existing static-taken override. In EX, when a\\nforward branch resolves, update the corresponding entry (set to branch_taken).\\nThis should shave mispredicts on biased forward branches with negligible\\narea/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.68, \"delta_pct\": -1.97, \"vs_baseline\": 14.8, \"fmax_mhz\": 137.53, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4235852, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10802, \"ff\": 2065, \"seeds\": [135.92, 137.53, 142.43], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:16:06.573026Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 12, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r12s2 (regression, -1.97%): A 32-entry 1-bit BHT defaulting to not-taken regressed CoreMark because sporadic taken forward branches poison their entry, causing repeated mispredicts on subsequent not-taken instances until the bit flips back \\u2014 worse than the static fall-through baseline.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r13s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 13, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 13}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Inline 16-entry GShare forward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static+RAS predictor already covers backward branches (taken),\\nJAL (taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). The only remaining mispredictions\\ncome from forward conditional branches, which are always predicted not-taken.\\nA prior 32-entry 1-bit BHT showed a tiny IPC improvement (~0.23 %) but\\nregressed overall fitness because aliasing poisoned entries and the extra\\narea hurt Fmax. A prior 16-entry PC-only bimodal produced exactly zero\\ndelta, strongly suggesting it was DCE\\u2019d due to new-module integration risk.\\nGShare XORs the PC with a global history register, which reduces aliasing\\nand can capture inter-branch correlation for the same silicon cost as a\\npure PC-indexed table. Keeping the state inline in existing files eliminates\\nthe integration/DCE risk that killed the bimodal attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static+RAS predictor already covers backward branches (taken),\\nJAL (taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). The only remaining mispredictions\\ncome from forward conditional branches, which are always predicted not-taken.\\nA prior 32-entry 1-bit BHT showed a tiny IPC improvement (~0.23 %) but\\nregressed overall fitness because aliasing poisoned entries and the extra\\narea hurt Fmax. A prior 16-entry PC-only bimodal produced exactly zero\\ndelta, strongly suggesting it was DCE\\u2019d due to new-module integration risk.\\nGShare XORs the PC with a global history register, which reduces aliasing\\nand can capture inter-branch correlation for the same silicon cost as a\\npure PC-indexed table. Keeping the state inline in existing files eliminates\\nthe integration/DCE risk that killed the bimodal attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-bit Global History Register (GHR) and a 16-entry array of 2-bit\\nsaturating counters directly inside if_stage.sv (no new module). For every\\nconditional branch that is NOT already handled by the static/RAS predictors\\n(i.e. forward B-type branches), compute the PHT index as pc[5:2] ^ ghr and\\npredict taken when the counter MSB is 1. All existing predictions (JAL,\\nbackward branches, RAS returns) keep their current priority and behaviour.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, on every resolved conditional branch (forward or backward),\\nshift the actual branch_taken bit into the GHR (LSB in, MSB out) and update\\nthe indexed 2-bit counter: increment if taken, decrement if not taken,\\nsaturating at 0 and 3. Wire only the update path (ghr_update, pht_we,\\npht_index, pht_inc) through core.sv. The total state is just 64 FFs for\\nthe PHT + 4 FFs for the GHR, small enough to keep area and timing impact\\nnegligible while learning the biased forward branches that the static\\npredictor currently misses.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-bit GHR register and 16x2-bit PHT array inline. Compute\\npht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr for forward conditional branches. Drive\\npredict_taken from the PHT MSB when the branch is forward; otherwise\\nkeep existing static/RAS priority. Update the GHR on the clock edge\\nwhen a branch-update signal arrives from EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Export ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index, and pht_taken signals. On every\\nresolved conditional branch (branch_taken valid this cycle), drive\\npht_we high, pht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr (pc comes from the EX-stage\\nin.pc), and pht_taken = actual branch direction. Also drive ghr_update\\nso the IF stage can shift the new bit into its GHR register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new GShare update signals (ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index,\\npht_taken) between ex_stage and if_stage. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-bit GHR register and 16x2-bit PHT array inline. Compute\\npht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr for forward conditional branches. Drive\\npredict_taken from the PHT MSB when the branch is forward; otherwise\\nkeep existing static/RAS priority. Update the GHR on the clock edge\\nwhen a branch-update signal arrives from EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Export ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index, and pht_taken signals. On every\\nresolved conditional branch (branch_taken valid this cycle), drive\\npht_we high, pht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr (pc comes from the EX-stage\\nin.pc), and pht_taken = actual branch direction. Also drive ghr_update\\nso the IF stage can shift the new bit into its GHR register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new GShare update signals (ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index,\\npht_taken) between ex_stage and if_stage. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:55:29.581811Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 13, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r13s2 (regression, +0.00%): Even with DCE risk eliminated by inlining, a 16-entry GShare forward-branch predictor yielded zero fitness delta, indicating CoreMark's sparse forward conditional branches offer no measurable IPC headroom beyond the static+RAS baseline on this microarchitecture.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\n, which hurt Fmax and erased the IPC gain. Word loads (LW) are\\nby far the most common and require no shift or extension\\u2014the correct value is\\nalready the raw 32-bit dmem_rdata word. Forwarding only LW removes the slow\\nbyte/halfword extraction from the critical path while recovering most of the\\ntheoretical IPC improvement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard because the\\nloaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register. CoreMark's hot paths\\n(list traversal, matrix kernels) contain many back-to-back LW-then-ALU and\\nLW-then-SW patterns. A prior unrestricted MEM-to-EX forwarding attempt\\nsign-extended all load widths inside the bypass path; the variable byte-shift\\nlogic created a long combinational delay from dmem_rdata through the operand\\nmux to the ALU, which hurt Fmax and erased the IPC gain. Word loads (LW) are\\nby far the most common and require no shift or extension\\u2014the correct value is\\nalready the raw 32-bit dmem_rdata word. Forwarding only LW removes the slow\\nbyte/halfword extraction from the critical path while recovering most of the\\ntheoretical IPC improvement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source that drives the raw\\ndmem_rdata word straight into the EX-stage operand muxes, but only when the\\ninstruction currently in MEM is an LW (ctrl.mem_read && ctrl.mem_width==2'd2).\\nUpdate forward_unit to emit a new select code (2'b11) for this case. Update\\nex_stage to mux the new source into rs1/rs2. Update hazard_unit to suppress\\nthe load-use stall only for word loads; byte and halfword loads continue to\\nstall exactly as before. Because the bypassed value is a plain 32-bit word,\\nno shift, mask, or sign-extend logic sits on the forwarding path, keeping the\\ncritical path short.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read and ex_mem_mem_width inputs. Extend the per-rs\\npriority chains so that when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 &&\\nex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read && ex_mem_mem_width==2'd2,\\noutput the new forwarding code 2'b11. The existing EX_MEM (2'b01) and\\nMEM_WB (2'b10) priorities remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1 and rs2 forwarding\\nmuxes with a fourth option: when the select is 2'b11, drive the operand\\nfrom fwd_mem_load instead of the existing sources. Ensure the ALU\\noperand selection (alu_a / alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as\\nbefore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a fwd_load_data output port. Drive it with dmem_rdata when\\nin.ctrl.mem_read && in.ctrl.mem_width==2'd2, otherwise drive 32'b0.\\nAll existing dmem address, write-data, and byte-mask logic remains\\nuntouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-bit id_ex_mem_width input. Modify load_use_hazard so it is\\nasserted only when the load in EX is NOT a word load\\n(id_ex_mem_width != 2'd2). For LW, the stall is suppressed because\\nthe MEM-to-EX forwarding path supplies the correct data to the\\ndependent instruction in EX. All other stall/flush logic is unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect\\nex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read and ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_width to forward_unit.\\nConnect id_ex_w.ctrl.mem_width to hazard_unit. No top-level port or\\nRVFI changes are required.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read and ex_mem_mem_width inputs. Extend the per-rs\\npriority chains so that when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 &&\\nex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read && ex_mem_mem_width==2'd2,\\noutput the new forwarding code 2'b11. The existing EX_MEM (2'b01) and\\nMEM_WB (2'b10) priorities remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1 and rs2 forwarding\\nmuxes with a fourth option: when the select is 2'b11, drive the operand\\nfrom fwd_mem_load instead of the existing sources. Ensure the ALU\\noperand selection (alu_a / alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as\\nbefore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a fwd_load_data output port. Drive it with dmem_rdata when\\nin.ctrl.mem_read && in.ctrl.mem_width==2'd2, otherwise drive 32'b0.\\nAll existing dmem address, write-data, and byte-mask logic remains\\nuntouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-bit id_ex_mem_width input. Modify load_use_hazard so it is\\nasserted only when the load in EX is NOT a word load\\n(id_ex_mem_width != 2'd2). For LW, the stall is suppressed because\\nthe MEM-to-EX forwarding path supplies the correct data to the\\ndependent instruction in EX. All other stall/flush logic is unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect\\nex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read and ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_width to forward_unit.\\nConnect id_ex_w.ctrl.mem_width to hazard_unit. No top-level port or\\nRVFI changes are required.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:11:32.459668Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r10s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r11s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r11s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r11s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"1-entry skid buffer in IF to decouple fetch from back-end stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer inside `if_stage.sv` consisting of a single\\n`if_id_t` register and a valid bit.  When the downstream ID stage is stalled\\n(`stall_id` asserted) and the buffer is empty, the buffer latches the current\\nvalid fetch bundle.  When the buffer is valid it drives the stage `out` port\\ninstead of the raw combinational fetch.  The buffer is cleared on reset,\\nredirect, or `flush_if`.  Restructure `hazard_unit.sv` so that `stall_if`\\nonly asserts when `imem_ready` is low OR when the buffer is already full\\nduring a back-end stall (`load_use_hazard || dmem_stall`).  `flush_if`\\nasserts only on `redirect` or on `imem_stall` when the buffer is empty.\\nLeave `stall_id`, `flush_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` unchanged.\\nWire the new `buf_valid` status signal and the existing `stall_id` signal\\nthrough `core.sv`.  No other RTL files are modified.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (`if_id_t` register + valid bit).  Capture the\\ncurrent valid fetch when `stall_id` is asserted and the buffer is empty.\\nOutput the buffered instruction when valid; otherwise bypass the\\ncombinational fetch path.  Clear the buffer on reset, redirect, or\\n`flush_if`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a `buf_valid` input.  Modify `stall_if` to assert only on\\n`imem_stall` or when `(load_use_hazard || dmem_stall) && buf_valid`.\\nModify `flush_if` to assert only on `redirect` or\\n`(imem_stall && !buf_valid)`.  Leave `stall_id`, `flush_id`,\\n`stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Declare `logic buf_valid` and wire it from `if_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\nAlso wire the existing `stall_id` net into `if_stage` as a new\\n`stall_id` input so the buffer knows when to capture.  No other\\ntop-level changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:46:28.944830Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 11, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r11s1 (regression, +0.00%): A 1-entry IF skid buffer cannot improve IPC when the benchmark is back-end bound by EX/MEM-stage hazards and multi-cycle dmem stalls; front-end decoupling only creates slack that the stalled back-end cannot absorb.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r11s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r11s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r11s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r11s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 11}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r12s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 12}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry pending-store slot to decouple store retirement from dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a 1-entry store_slot module between the MEM stage and the\\nexternal dmem port.  When mem_stage detects a valid, aligned store\\nto normal RAM (below 0x00100000) and the slot is empty, it retires\\nthe store into the slot and de-asserts mem_wait so the pipeline\\ncontinues.  The slot drains to the dmem port whenever dmemReady is\\nhigh.  Younger loads and non-bufferable stores wait in MEM while the\\nslot is valid, preserving load-after-store ordering.  Adapt\\nhazard_unit to stall on the precise mem_wait signal exported by\\nmem_stage instead of the coarse dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op\\ncombination.  This structural decoupling recovers cycles lost to\\nstore-related dmem stalls without touching the ALU or fetch paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry pending-store buffer (valid, addr, wdata, wmask) with enqueue/drain interface.  On enqueue the store retires; on drain the physical write goes to the dmem port when dmemReady is high. Straight shift-register design adapted from the proven cores/v1 store_slot.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store-slot interface ports (enqueue, addr, wdata, wmask) and a precise mem_wait output.  Detect bufferable stores: valid, aligned, legal, normal-RAM (addr < 0x00100000) writes.  When a bufferable store hits a dmem stall and the slot is empty, assert enqueue and keep mem_wait low.  For loads and non-bufferable stores mem_wait follows !dmem_ready; when the slot is already valid mem_wait is high so younger memory ops wait for ordering. All existing load-extraction and RVFI mem field logic stays unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the coarse dmem_stall logic (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op) with a single mem_wait input driven by mem_stage.  Stall_if, stall_id, flush_id, stall_ex_mem and hold_mem_wb all key off mem_wait exactly as they currently key off dmem_stall, preserving the existing load-use and redirect bubble semantics.  Remove the now-unused dmem_ready and ex_mem_mem_op ports.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_slot and wire its enqueue/drain signals between mem_stage and the external dmem port.  Add a top-level combinational arbiter that gives the slot priority: when store_slot_valid is asserted the external dmem port is driven by the slot drain data, otherwise by the live mem_stage outputs. Wire the new mem_wait signal from mem_stage into hazard_unit. Keep all RVFI, regfile, and forwarding wiring untouched.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 305.1, \"delta_pct\": -7.89, \"vs_baseline\": 7.88, \"fmax_mhz\": 128.53, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4212703, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10075, \"ff\": 2033, \"seeds\": [126.9, 129.22, 128.53], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:19:44.287568Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 12, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 1-bit BHT for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped branch history table with 1-bit saturating\\ncounters indexed by PC[6:2]. In IF, forward conditional branches consult the\\nBHT: if the bit is 1, predict taken (target is the existing b_target);\\nbackward branches keep their existing static-taken override. In EX, when a\\nforward branch resolves, update the corresponding entry (set to branch_taken).\\nThis should shave mispredicts on biased forward branches with negligible\\narea/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT update output signals (index, enable, taken) on forward branch resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate BHT module and wire read/update ports between IF and EX stages.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.68, \"delta_pct\": -1.97, \"vs_baseline\": 14.8, \"fmax_mhz\": 137.53, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4235852, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10802, \"ff\": 2065, \"seeds\": [135.92, 137.53, 142.43], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:16:06.573026Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 12, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r12s2 (regression, -1.97%): A 32-entry 1-bit BHT defaulting to not-taken regressed CoreMark because sporadic taken forward branches poison their entry, causing repeated mispredicts on subsequent not-taken instances until the bit flips back \\u2014 worse than the static fall-through baseline.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r13s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 13, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 13}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Inline 16-entry GShare forward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static+RAS predictor already covers backward branches (taken),\\nJAL (taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). The only remaining mispredictions\\ncome from forward conditional branches, which are always predicted not-taken.\\nA prior 32-entry 1-bit BHT showed a tiny IPC improvement (~0.23 %) but\\nregressed overall fitness because aliasing poisoned entries and the extra\\narea hurt Fmax. A prior 16-entry PC-only bimodal produced exactly zero\\ndelta, strongly suggesting it was DCE\\u2019d due to new-module integration risk.\\nGShare XORs the PC with a global history register, which reduces aliasing\\nand can capture inter-branch correlation for the same silicon cost as a\\npure PC-indexed table. Keeping the state inline in existing files eliminates\\nthe integration/DCE risk that killed the bimodal attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static+RAS predictor already covers backward branches (taken),\\nJAL (taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). The only remaining mispredictions\\ncome from forward conditional branches, which are always predicted not-taken.\\nA prior 32-entry 1-bit BHT showed a tiny IPC improvement (~0.23 %) but\\nregressed overall fitness because aliasing poisoned entries and the extra\\narea hurt Fmax. A prior 16-entry PC-only bimodal produced exactly zero\\ndelta, strongly suggesting it was DCE\\u2019d due to new-module integration risk.\\nGShare XORs the PC with a global history register, which reduces aliasing\\nand can capture inter-branch correlation for the same silicon cost as a\\npure PC-indexed table. Keeping the state inline in existing files eliminates\\nthe integration/DCE risk that killed the bimodal attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-bit Global History Register (GHR) and a 16-entry array of 2-bit\\nsaturating counters directly inside if_stage.sv (no new module). For every\\nconditional branch that is NOT already handled by the static/RAS predictors\\n(i.e. forward B-type branches), compute the PHT index as pc[5:2] ^ ghr and\\npredict taken when the counter MSB is 1. All existing predictions (JAL,\\nbackward branches, RAS returns) keep their current priority and behaviour.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, on every resolved conditional branch (forward or backward),\\nshift the actual branch_taken bit into the GHR (LSB in, MSB out) and update\\nthe indexed 2-bit counter: increment if taken, decrement if not taken,\\nsaturating at 0 and 3. Wire only the update path (ghr_update, pht_we,\\npht_index, pht_inc) through core.sv. The total state is just 64 FFs for\\nthe PHT + 4 FFs for the GHR, small enough to keep area and timing impact\\nnegligible while learning the biased forward branches that the static\\npredictor currently misses.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-bit GHR register and 16x2-bit PHT array inline. Compute\\npht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr for forward conditional branches. Drive\\npredict_taken from the PHT MSB when the branch is forward; otherwise\\nkeep existing static/RAS priority. Update the GHR on the clock edge\\nwhen a branch-update signal arrives from EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Export ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index, and pht_taken signals. On every\\nresolved conditional branch (branch_taken valid this cycle), drive\\npht_we high, pht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr (pc comes from the EX-stage\\nin.pc), and pht_taken = actual branch direction. Also drive ghr_update\\nso the IF stage can shift the new bit into its GHR register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new GShare update signals (ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index,\\npht_taken) between ex_stage and if_stage. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-bit GHR register and 16x2-bit PHT array inline. Compute\\npht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr for forward conditional branches. Drive\\npredict_taken from the PHT MSB when the branch is forward; otherwise\\nkeep existing static/RAS priority. Update the GHR on the clock edge\\nwhen a branch-update signal arrives from EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Export ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index, and pht_taken signals. On every\\nresolved conditional branch (branch_taken valid this cycle), drive\\npht_we high, pht_index = pc[5:2] ^ ghr (pc comes from the EX-stage\\nin.pc), and pht_taken = actual branch direction. Also drive ghr_update\\nso the IF stage can shift the new bit into its GHR register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new GShare update signals (ghr_update, pht_we, pht_index,\\npht_taken) between ex_stage and if_stage. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:55:29.581811Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 13, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r13s2 (regression, +0.00%): Even with DCE risk eliminated by inlining, a 16-entry GShare forward-branch predictor yielded zero fitness delta, indicating CoreMark's sparse forward conditional branches offer no measurable IPC headroom beyond the static+RAS baseline on this microarchitecture.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Read recent log entries","truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencod