{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778745220510,"sessionID":"ses_1da888381ffeERBNiSDObuLSW4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"functions.read:8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":33,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"1-entry skid buffer in IF to decouple fetch from back-end stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. T