{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778749245844,"sessionID":"ses_1da4a0c95ffefe50mqExv17gYU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"functions.grep:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"mul|div|pipeline|multi-cycle|DSP|latency","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"*.jsonl"},"output":"Found 21 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multi-cycle iterative divider to break ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths in alu.sv with a compact 32-cycle\\niterative divider (shift-and-subtract / non-restoring) that exposes a start/done\\ninterface. The ex_stage will detect divide ops and hold the EX/MEM register while\\nthe divider runs, asserting a new div_busy signal back to the hazard unit. The\\nhazard unit stalls the entire pipeline upstream (IF, ID, EX) during division,\\nanalogous to a dmem stall. Non-divide ALU ops remain combinational single-cycle.\\nThe ALTOPS formal branch stays unchanged so riscv-formal still sees combinational\\nbehaviour. Removing the massive combinational divider from the ALU output ...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor to IF stage\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a combinational static predictor in the IF stage with two\\nrules: (1) JAL is always predicted taken, and (2) conditional branches\\nare predicted backward-taken, forward-not-taken (BTFN).  The predictor\\ndecodes the instruction currently on the imem bus, extracts the B-type\\nor J-type immediate, and computes the target address as PC+imm.  When a\\ntaken prediction is made, the IF stage overrides next_pc with the\\ntarget instead of PC+4.  The EX stage recomputes the same prediction\\nfrom the instruction in EX; it asserts redirect only on mispredict\\n(predicted taken but not taken, or vice versa).  This removes the\\nflush penalty for correctly predicted branches and jumps without\\nrequiring any extra pipeline registers or state RAM, keeping LUT usage\\nwithin the remaining budget....\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage static predictor: backward branches and JAL always taken\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational prediction logic to if_stage.sv that detects JAL (always\\ntaken) and backward B-type branches (negative offset, i.e. imm[31]=1) in the\\nfetched instruction, computes the target address from the immediate, and\\nsteers next_pc to the target when the target is 4-byte aligned. Extend the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles (core_pkg.sv) with predict_taken and predict_target\\nfields. Modify ex_stage.sv to treat a mismatch between predicted and actual\\noutcome as the redirect condition (mispredict), suppressing the flush on\\ncorrect predictions. This turns the common-case loop back-edge and function\\ncall from a 2-cycle bubble into zero penalty.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target ...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-stage load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source: the MEM-stage\\nsign/zero-extended load_data (computed combinationally from dmem_rdata and\\nthe byte-offset in ex_mem_w.alu_result). When the instruction currently in\\nMEM is a LOAD and its rd matches the rs1 or rs2 of the instruction in EX,\\nforward the load_data instead of the ALU result. Update forward_unit to\\nencode this as a new select value (e.g. 2'b11). Update ex_stage to mux the\\nnew source into the rs1/rs2 operand paths. Remove the load-use stall term\\nfrom hazard_unit entirely: the dependent instruction now enters EX on the\\ncycle the LOAD enters MEM, and the bypass supplies the correct data\\ncombinationally. The existing dmem_stall freeze (stall_ex_mem) safely c...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark's matrix and list workloads are heavy with load-to-ALU\\ndependency chains (e.g. lw followed by add/mul). The current 5-stage\\npipeline stalls the entire front-end for one cycle on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM stage\\ncompletes and writes the MEM/WB register. A combinational bypass\\nfrom the MEM-stage load-data extractor to the EX-stage operand muxes\\nallows dependent ALU instructions to execute in the cycle immediately\\nafter the load enters MEM, removing the stall for the common case.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational forwarding path from mem_stage's load_data\\n(post byte-align and sign-extension) to the ex_stage operand muxes.\\nExtend forward_unit to select this source (encoding 2'b11) when the\\ninstruction in EX/MEM is a load and its rd matches the EX-stage rs.\\nModify the hazard_unit to suppress the load-use stall for\\nnon-control-flow instructions: only assert the stall when the\\ninstruction in IF/ID is a branch or JALR, preventing a mispredict\\nredirect from being computed on invalid data during a dmem stall.\\nAll other dependents (ALU, LOAD, STORE) proceed without stalling and\\nconsume the forwarded load data.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data as a new fwd_load_data output port.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input and emit forwarding select 2'b11 when EX/...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly handles JAL and backward branches,\\nbut all JALR returns are unpredicted (fall-through), causing a 2-cycle\\npipeline flush on every function return. CoreMark contains many function\\ncalls and returns; eliminating these mispredictions should improve IPC\\nwith minimal area/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In IF, detect JALR with rs1=x1\\nand imm=0 as a return; predict taken to RAS top if the stack is non-empty.\\nIn ID, pop the RAS when a predicted return is captured into the ID/EX\\nregister (gated by !flush so wrong-path returns never corrupt the stack).\\nIn ID, detect JAL/JALR writing x1 as a call and push PC+4 to the RAS\\n(also gated by !flush, and safe because wrong-path instructions are\\nflushed before they reach ID). The RAS is purely a performance\\noptimization; mispredictions are still corrected by the existing EX-stage\\nredirect logic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 8-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS ports; detect return-pattern JALR (rs1=x1, imm=0); predict taken to RAS top when stack is non-empty; otherwise fall through.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS push/pop ports; detect call (JAL/JALR writing x1) and push PC+4 on capture into ID/EX; detect return and pop RAS on capture when the return was predicted taken; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire push/pop/addr/top/empty between IF, ID and ...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Remove redundant EX-stage adder by reusing IF precomputed branch target\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"In ex_stage.sv, replace all occurrences of (in.pc + in.imm) for branch_target and\\nfor the non-JALR jump_target with the existing in.predict_target field that was\\nprecomputed in IF stage. This removes a 32-bit adder from the branch-resolve and\\nmisalign-check paths in EX. In alu.sv, guard each 64-bit product (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su) so it is computed only when the specific ALU op that consumes it is\\nselected, eliminating unnecessary multiplier switching and helping sy...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\\nalgorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\\nstage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\\ndecodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\\ndiv_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\\nsimplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\\nremoves the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\\nsignificantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient ...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with inlined iterative multi-cycle FSM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from alu.sv (keep the\\nALTOPS formal branch unchanged). Implement a 32-cycle shift-subtract\\ndivider as a local always_ff FSM directly inside ex_stage.sv\\u2014no new\\nmodule file is required. The FSM converts signed operands to magnitude,\\nperforms unsigned shift-subtract for 32 cycles, then restores the sign\\nfor DIV/REM. When a divide opcode is decoded in EX, ex_stage starts the\\nFSM and asserts div_busy. hazard_unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the FSM finishes. The result is\\ncaptured into the EX/MEM register on the final cycle. Because the ALU\\nmodule loses its clockless divider, the cocotb ALU unit tests for\\nDIV/REM must be removed.\\n\", \"expected_i...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with proven PicoRV32 iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration t...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly handles backward branches and JAL, and\\nthe 4-entry RAS covers returns. Forward conditional branches remain predicted\\nnot-taken. A prior 16-entry bimodal attempt produced zero delta, likely because\\npure PC indexing suffered severe aliasing in the small table or because the\\nnew-module integration was not wired correctly. A GShare predictor XORs the PC\\nwith a global history register, reducing aliasing and capturing inter-branch\\ncorrelation that a PC-only table cannot. CoreMark's state-machine and\\nlist-traversal kernels contain correlated forward branches; learning these\\npatterns can eliminate residual mispredict stalls with only ~70 flip-flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry Pattern History Table (2-bit saturating counters) and a 5-bit\\nGlobal History Register (GHR) directly into if_stage.sv. Index the PHT with\\npc[6:2] ^ ghr. For every conditional branch, predict taken when the counter\\nMSB is 1; keep the existing static predictions for JAL, backward branches, and\\nRAS returns untouched. In ex_stage.sv, export the actual branch outcome and\\nPC[6:2] back to IF. On every resolved branch, update the GHR by shifting in\\nthe actual taken bit, and update the indexed PHT counter (increment if taken,\\ndecrement if not, saturating at 0 and 3). Implement everything inline in\\nexisting files to avoid new-module integration risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 5-bit GHR register and 32x2-bit PHT array. Use pc[6:2] ^ ghr to index\\nthe PHT and drive predict_...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC+4 in ID stage and pipeline to EX to eliminate redundant adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a pc_plus4 field to id_ex_t (core_pkg.sv). In id_stage.sv latch\\nreg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 alongside the existing ID/EX state. In\\nex_stage.sv replace every occurrence of in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4:\\n(1) alu_result for JAL/JALR, (2) pc_next on misalign trap, (3) redirect_target\\nwhen the branch/jump is not taken. This removes three 32-bit adders from the\\nEX stage at the cost of one adder in ID and 32 extra flip-flops in the ID/EX\\nregister. Because the ID/EX capture path is not the current critical path,\\nthe net effect should be a small Fmax improvement (2-4 MHz) with zero IPC\\nchange.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/co...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline stalls the front-end (PC and combinational IF/ID output) on\\nevery back-end stall: load-use hazards, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. During a\\nload-use bubble or a dmem freeze, the fetch unit sits idle even though the\\ninstruction memory might be ready. A tiny instruction buffer between IF and ID\\nallows the front-end to prefetch instructions while the back-end is stalled,\\nand it can hide single-cycle imem stalls by serving a buffered instruction to\\nID when the bus is not ready. CoreMark spends a noticeable fraction of cycles\\nin load-use bubbles and random memory stalls; decoupling fetch from decode\\nturns many of those dead front-end cycles into productive prefetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer inside if_stage.sv that sits between the raw\\ninstruction fetch and the IF/ID output.  IF pushes a fetched if_id_t bundle\\ninto the buffer whenever imem_ready is high and the buffer is not full.  ID\\npops from the buffer head every cycle the buffer is non-empty.  When the\\nbuffer is empty the output bypasses directly from the current fetch, preserving\\nthe existing combinational path.  Restructure hazard_unit.sv so that stall_if\\nonly asserts when imem_ready is low AND the buffer is full, removing load_use\\nand dmem_stall from the IF stall logic.  ID stall (stall_id) gains a new term\\nthat asserts when the buffer is empty, ensuring ID never decodes a non-existent\\ninstruction.  The buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never\\npollute the queue.  This is a pure structural decoupling: no new modules, just\\ntwo ...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle imem stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. This is a pure\\nstructural decoupling with no ISA or pipeline-depth change.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer inside `if_stage.sv` consisting of a single\\n`if_id_t` register and a valid bit. When the downstream ID stage is stalled\\n(`stall_id` asserted) the buffer latches the current valid fetch bundle;\\nwhen valid it drives the `out` port instead of the raw combinational fetch.\\nThe buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never pollute\\nit.  Restructure `hazard_unit.sv` so that `stall_if` only asserts when the\\nbuffer is already full (second consecutive ID stall) or on multi-cycle dmem\\nstalls, and so that `flush_if` is suppressed during single-cycle imem stalls\\nwhen the buffer can cover the ready-drop. Wire the buffer status signals\\nthrough `core.sv`. This removes the front-end idle cycles that currently\\noccur during load-use bubbles and one-cycle imem stalls.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer (if_id_t regist...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"1-entry indirect JALR target cache in IF stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend if_stage.sv with a 1-entry indirect-JALR target cache\\n(jalr_cache_valid + jalr_cache_target[31:0]).  In the IF-stage prediction\\ncombinational logic, treat any JALR that is not a return (rd=x0 & rs1=x1) as\\ntaken when the cache is valid, steering next_pc to jalr_cache_target.  When\\nthe ...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX raw-word forwarding for LW-only to cut load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard because the\\nloaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register. CoreMark's hot paths\\n(list traversal, matrix kernels) contain many back-to-back LW-then-ALU and\\nLW-then-SW patterns. A prior unrestricted MEM-to-EX forwarding attempt\\nsign-extended all load widths inside the bypass path; the variable byte-shift\\nlogic created a long combinational delay from dmem_rdata through the operand\\nmux to the ALU, which hurt Fmax and erased the IPC gain. Word loads (LW) are\\nby far the most common and require no shift or extension\\u2014the correct value is\\nalready the raw 32-bit dmem_rdata word. Forwarding only LW removes the slow\\nbyte/halfword extraction from the critical path while recovering most of the\\ntheoretical IPC improvement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard because the\\nloaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register. CoreMark's hot paths\\n(list traversal, matrix kernels) contain many back-to-back LW-then-ALU and\\nLW-then-SW patterns. A prior unrestricted MEM-to-EX forwarding attempt\\nsign-extended all load widths inside the bypass path; the variable byte-shift\\nlogic created a long combinational delay from dmem_rdata through the operand\\nmux to the ALU, which hurt Fmax and erased the IPC gain. Word loads (LW) are\\nby far the most common and require no shift or extension\\u2014the correct value is\\nalready the raw 32-bit dmem_rdata word. Forwarding only LW removes the slow\\nbyte/halfword extraction from the critical path while recovering most of the\\ntheoretical IPC improvement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source that drives the raw\\ndmem_rdata word straight into the EX-stage operand muxes, but only when the\\ninstruction currently in MEM ...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"1-entry skid buffer in IF to decouple fetch from back-end stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline front-end stalls the PC on every load-use hazard and dmem stall,\\nand emits NOPs on every imem ready-drop. CoreMark cosim injects ~22% random\\nimem/dmem stalls. A tiny 1-entry skid buffer decouples fetch from decode: it\\ncaptures the fetched instruction when the back-end cannot accept it, allowing\\nthe PC to advance and prefetch the next instruction. On a subsequent\\nsingle-cycle stall the buffered instruction keeps the decode stage fed,\\nturning an otherwise dead cycle into productive work. Two prior structural\\nattempts at this idea were rolled back because the implementation agent\\ntouched files outside the allowed change list; by scoping the hypothesis to\\nexactly three files we eliminate that risk and finally evaluate the idea.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 1-entry skid buffer inside `if_stage.sv` consisting of a single\\n`if_id_t` register and a valid bit.  When the downstream ID stage is stalled\\n(`stall_id` asserted) and the buffer is empty, the buffer latches the current\\nvalid fetch bundle.  When the buffer is valid it drives ...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry pending-store slot to decouple store retirement from dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline pipeline stalls the entire back-end on every dmem stall,\\nincluding stores. CoreMark contains many stores (matrix writes, list\\npointer updates, stack traffic). When a store reaches MEM while\\ndmemReady is low, the front-end and back-end freeze until the bus\\nclears, turning those cycles into dead time. A 1-entry pending-store\\nslot lets aligned normal-RAM stores retire immediately into a buffer\\nand drain later when the bus is free. Subsequent non-memory\\ninstructions can execute in the shadow of the pending store,\\nrecovering cycles that are currently lost. The concept is proven in\\nthe `cores/v1` RTL and carries near-zero Fmax risk because the slot\\nis only a handful of registers and a port-priority mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Integrate a 1-entry store_slot module between the MEM stage and the\\nexternal dmem port.  When mem_stage detects a valid, aligned store\\nto normal RAM (below 0x00100000) and the slot is empty, it retires\\nthe store into the slot and de-asserts mem_wait so the pipeline\\ncontinues.  The slot drains to the dmem port whenever ...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 1-bit BHT for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor handles backward loops (static taken), JAL (always taken),\\nand returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches remain unpredicted and\\nalways fall through. In CoreMark's control-flow-heavy inner loops (state\\nmachine, list traversal), some forward branches are biased taken; each\\nmispredict wastes a full pipeline bubble. A 32-entry 1-bit BHT adds <10 LUTs\\nand near-zero delay, offering dynamic correction for these branches without\\ntouching any critical EX/MEM path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped branch history table with 1-bit saturating\\ncounters indexed by PC[6:2]. In IF, forward conditional branches consult the\\nBHT: if the bit is 1, predict taken (target is the existing b_target);\\nbackward branches keep their existing static-taken override. In EX, when a\\nforward branch resolves, update the corresponding entry (set to branch_taken).\\nThis should shave mispredicts on biased forward branches with negligible\\narea/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bht.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-entry 1-bit BHT module with combinational read and synchronous update.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BHT read interface; use BHT output for forward branch predict_taken.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", ...","metadata":{"matches":21,"truncated":false},"title":"mul|div|pipeline|multi-cycle|DSP|latency","time":{"start":1778749245821,"end":1778749245842}},"id":"prt_e25b786c6001TTxCak4mk7RSAq","sessionID":"ses_1da4a0c95ffefe50mqExv17gYU","messageID":"msg_e25b5f3a9001YTFlsJVHsBm5W0"}}
