{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778751729951,"sessionID":"ses_1da23e9c5ffeelLZA5icmOJ2op","part":{"id":"prt_e25dd711c001hyPXaGB3uditsI","messageID":"msg_e25dd4ae70016zwcoWLeQK7Az4","sessionID":"ses_1da23e9c5ffeelLZA5icmOJ2op","snapshot":"671164bd667f2c62321c05741bc34eaffbb54e2b","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778751741093,"sessionID":"ses_1da23e9c5ffeelLZA5icmOJ2op","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -E '\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r[567]s1\"' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl -A 5","description":"Check divider hypothesis outcomes r5-r7"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with inlined iterative multi-cycle FSM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from alu.sv (keep the\\nALTOPS formal branch unchanged). Implement a 32-cycle shift-subtract\\ndivider as a local always_ff FSM directly inside ex_stage.sv\\u2014no new\\nmodule file is required. The FSM converts signed operands to magnitude,\\nperforms unsigned shift-subtract for 32 cycles, then restores the sign\\nfor DIV/REM. When a divide opcode is decoded in EX, ex_stage starts the\\nFSM and asserts div_busy. hazard_unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the FSM finishes. The result is\\ncaptured into the EX/MEM register on the final cycle. Because the ALU\\nmodule loses its clockless divider, the cocotb ALU unit tests for\\nDIV/REM must be removed.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases from the case\\nstatement; they now fall to default (output 32'b0). Keep the\\n`ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged so formal\\nverification continues to see combinational behaviour.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an inline 32-cycle shift-subtract divider FSM (always_ff)\\ninside ex_stage. On detecting a DIV/REM opcode, latch the operands,\\nrun 32 cycles of shift/subtract, and capture the final quotient or\\nremainder into the EX/MEM alu_result field. Assert a new div_busy\\noutput while the FSM is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update\\nwith !div_busy so the divide instruction stays in EX until done.\\nEnsure non-divide instructions continue to flow in a single cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Combine it with dmem_stall so that\\nstall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb are all asserted\\nwhile div_busy is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove or comment out all DIV/REM cocotb tests (div_signed,\\ndiv_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed,\\nrem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides)\\nbecause the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases from the case\\nstatement; they now fall to default (output 32'b0). Keep the\\n`ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged so formal\\nverification continues to see combinational behaviour.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an inline 32-cycle shift-subtract divider FSM (always_ff)\\ninside ex_stage. On detecting a DIV/REM opcode, latch the operands,\\nrun 32 cycles of shift/subtract, and capture the final quotient or\\nremainder into the EX/MEM alu_result field. Assert a new div_busy\\noutput while the FSM is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update\\nwith !div_busy so the divide instruction stays in EX until done.\\nEnsure non-divide instructions continue to flow in a single cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Combine it with dmem_stall so that\\nstall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb are all asserted\\nwhile div_busy is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove or comment out all DIV/REM cocotb tests (div_signed,\\ndiv_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed,\\nrem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides)\\nbecause the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry BTB to remove IF-stage target adder and extend branch coverage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 280.97, \"delta_pct\": -15.17, \"vs_baseline\": -0.65, \"fmax_mhz\": 118.62, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4221744, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 12328, \"ff\": 2983, \"seeds\": [118.62, 121.34, 116.46], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:27:55.029690Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r6s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r6s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r6s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r6s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with proven PicoRV32 iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from `alu.sv` (keep the\\n`RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch unchanged so formal verification still sees\\ncombinational behaviour). Adapt the `picorv32_pcpi_div` module from\\n`cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` into a new standalone `div_unit.sv` with a\\nsimplified interface: `start`, `op` (one-hot DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), `a`, `b`,\\n`result`, `busy`, `done`. Integrate the unit into the EX stage: when a divide\\nopcode is decoded, start `div_unit` and assert `div_busy`. Hold the EX/MEM\\nregister while `div_busy` is high; on `done` capture the result into\\n`reg_q.alu_result`. Extend `hazard_unit` to treat `div_busy` like\\n`dmem_stall`, freezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider finishes. Wire\\n`div_busy` through `core.sv`. The cocotb ALU unit tests for division must be\\nremoved because the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 15, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New module adapted from `cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` module `picorv32_pcpi_div`. Simplified to expose `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `result`, `busy`, `done`. Handles signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32IM. Keeps the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch from the original.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the case statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0`. Keep the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide opcodes and start `div_unit`. Assert a new `div_busy` output while the unit is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update with `!div_busy`; capture `div_unit.result` into `reg_q.alu_result` on the final cycle. Non-divide instructions continue single-cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Combine it with `dmem_stall` so that `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` are all asserted while `div_busy` is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate `div_unit`, wire its control/operand ports to the EX stage, and route the new `div_busy` signal from `ex_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove all DIV/REM cocotb tests because the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 15, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New module adapted from `cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` module `picorv32_pcpi_div`. Simplified to expose `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `result`, `busy`, `done`. Handles signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32IM. Keeps the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch from the original.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the case statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0`. Keep the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide opcodes and start `div_unit`. Assert a new `div_busy` output while the unit is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update with `!div_busy`; capture `div_unit.result` into `reg_q.alu_result` on the final cycle. Non-divide instructions continue single-cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Combine it with `dmem_stall` so that `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` are all asserted while `div_busy` is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate `div_unit`, wire its control/operand ports to the EX stage, and route the new `div_busy` signal from `ex_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove all DIV/REM cocotb tests because the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r6s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r6s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r6s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Copy `cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv` verbatim into `cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv`.\\nThe module exposes `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `busy`, `done`, `result` and\\nreferences the global ALU op constants defined in `core_pkg.sv` (which is\\nalready compiled first). Its internal logic is battle-tested and includes\\nthe required `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch.\\n\\nIn `alu.sv`, remove only the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`,\\n`ALU_REMU` cases from the `case (op)` statement so they fall to the\\n`default: out = 32'b0;` path. Leave the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`\\nbranch completely untouched so formal verification continues to see\\ncombinational behaviour for those opcodes.\\n\\nIn `ex_stage.sv`, integrate the divider exactly as v1 does:\\n- Add `is_div_op`, `div_request`, `div_start`, `div_busy`, `div_done`,\\n  `div_result_w`, `div_active_q`, `div_result_valid_q`, `div_result_q`,\\n  `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`, `div_complete`, and\\n  `div_result_selected` signals.\\n- Instantiate `div_unit` with `start=div_start`, `op=in.ctrl.alu_op`,\\n  `a=alu_a`, `b=alu_b`, connecting `busy`, `done`, and `result`.\\n- Set `div_request = in.valid && is_div_op && !in.ctrl.is_illegal &&\\n  !div_active_q`.\\n- Set `div_start = div_request && !stall`.\\n- Set `div_complete = div_active_q && (div_result_valid_q || div_done)`.\\n- Assert a new output `ex_long_busy = div_start || div_busy ||\\n  (div_active_q && !div_complete)`.\\n- In the first EX/MEM always_ff block: on `div_start`, latch `div_active_q`,\\n  save `in`, `rs1`, `rs2` into `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`.\\n  On `div_done && div_active_q`, capture `div_result_w` into\\n  `div_result_q` and set `div_result_valid_q`. On `div_complete && !stall`,\\n  clear `div_active_q` and `div_result_valid_q`.\\n- In the second EX/MEM always_ff block: add `else if (div_complete)` that\\n  writes the saved `div_in_q` state into `reg_q` with `alu_result` set to\\n  `div_result_selected`. Add `else if (div_start || div_active_q)` that\\n  injects a bubble (`reg_q <= '0`). Keep all existing non-divide logic\\n  unchanged.\\n\\nIn `hazard_unit.sv`, add an `ex_long_busy` input and include it in\\n`stall_if` and `stall_id` alongside the existing stall terms. Do NOT add it\\nto `flush_id` \\u2014 we want to hold the divide instruction in ID/EX, not clear\\nit.\\n\\nIn `core.sv`, wire the new `ex_long_busy` output from `ex_stage` to the\\nnew `ex_long_busy` input on `hazard_unit`.\\n\\nIn `test/test_alu.py`, delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/\\nREM/REMU opcodes through the ALU module: `div_signed`, `div_by_zero`,\\n`div_overflow`, `divu`, `divu_by_zero`, `rem_signed`, `rem_by_zero`,\\n`rem_overflow`, `remu`, `remu_by_zero`, and `back_to_back_divides`.\\nThe ALU no longer implements those opcodes, and the proven `div_unit.sv`\\nis verified by cosim and formal instead.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Copy cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv verbatim into this new file. The module is fully proven, includes RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS support, and references the global ALU op constants from core_pkg.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, ALU_REMU cases from the case statement so they fall to default out=32'b0. Keep the ALTOPS branch and all other ALU operations unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate div_unit exactly as cores/v1/rtl/ex_stage.sv does. Add the divider control FSM (is_div_op, div_start, div_active_q, etc.), instantiate div_unit with alu_a/alu_b operands, assert ex_long_busy while dividing, and modify the EX/MEM register logic to capture the saved instruction state on div_complete while emitting bubbles during the divide. Use bench naming (predict_taken, predict_target).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_long_busy input. Include it in stall_if and stall_id alongside the existing stall terms (load_use, imem_stall, dmem_stall). Do not add it to flush_id.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ex_long_busy output from ex_stage to the new ex_long_busy input on hazard_unit. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU opcodes (div_signed, div_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed, rem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides) because the ALU module no longer implements division or remainder.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Copy cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv verbatim into this new file. The module is fully proven, includes RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS support, and references the global ALU op constants from core_pkg.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, ALU_REMU cases from the case statement so they fall to default out=32'b0. Keep the ALTOPS branch and all other ALU operations unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate div_unit exactly as cores/v1/rtl/ex_stage.sv does. Add the divider control FSM (is_div_op, div_start, div_active_q, etc.), instantiate div_unit with alu_a/alu_b operands, assert ex_long_busy while dividing, and modify the EX/MEM register logic to capture the saved instruction state on div_complete while emitting bubbles during the divide. Use bench naming (predict_taken, predict_target).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_long_busy input. Include it in stall_if and stall_id alongside the existing stall terms (load_use, imem_stall, dmem_stall). Do not add it to flush_id.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ex_long_busy output from ex_stage to the new ex_long_busy input on hazard_unit. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU opcodes (div_signed, div_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed, rem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides) because the ALU module no longer implements division or remainder.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes \\u2014 Iterative Divider Integration\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- **Added `rtl/div_unit.sv`** \\u2014 copied verbatim from `cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv`. The module implements a 32-cycle shift-subtract divider with full RV32M semantics (signed/unsigned DIV/REM, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow) and includes the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch for formal compatibility.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/alu.sv`** \\u2014 removed the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the `case (op)` statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0;`. The `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch was left completely untouched, preserving the combinational ALTOPS substitution that formal verification expects.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/ex_stage.sv`** \\u2014 integrated the divider exactly as `cores/v1` does:\\n  - Added `ex_long_busy` output.\\n  - Added divider control signals (`is_div_op`, `div_request`, `div_start`, `div_busy`, `div_done`, `div_result_w`, `div_active_q`, `div_result_valid_q`, `div_result_q`, `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`, `div_complete`, `div_result_selected`).\\n  - Instantiated `div_unit` with operand mux outputs `alu_a` / `alu_b`.\\n  - Split the EX/MEM register logic into two `always_ff` blocks: one for divider state, one for `reg_q`. The `reg_q` block now emits bubbles (`reg_q <= '0`) while a divide is active, and on `div_complete` it writes the saved instruction state with `alu_result` set to the divider result.\\n  - Preserved all existing bench-specific branch/mispredict logic (uses `predict_taken` / `predict_target`, not v1's `predicted_taken` / `predicted_target`).\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/hazard_unit.sv`** \\u2014 added `ex_long_busy` input and included it in `stall_if` and `stall_id` alongside the existing stall terms. `flush_id` was intentionally left unchanged so the divide instruction stays in ID/EX rather than being cleared.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/core.sv`** \\u2014 declared `logic ex_long_busy` and wired it from `ex_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\n\\n- **Modified `test/test_alu.py`** \\u2014 removed all cocotb tests that exercised DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU through the ALU module, plus the now-unused `_check_div` helper and the now-unused opcode imports. The ALU no longer implements those opcodes; divider correctness is covered by cosim and formal.\\n\\n## Deviations from hypothesis\\n\\nNone. The implementation follows the hypothesis verbatim, using bench naming conventions where they differ from v1.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- The divider is 32-cycle iterative. CoreMark contains virtually no integer divisions, so IPC impact is negligible, but a pathological program with back-to-back divides will see a large slowdown.\\n- `div_unit.sv` references global ALU op constants (`ALU_DIV`, etc.) from `core_pkg.sv`. This file is compiled first in all build flows, so the reference is safe.\\n- The `div_in_q` latch saves the entire `id_ex_t` struct. Some fields (e.g., `predict_taken`) are unused when the saved instruction is later written to `reg_q`. Verilator lint is suppressed around `div_in_q` to avoid `UNUSEDSIGNAL` warnings.\\n\\n## Local verification status\\n\\n- **Verilator lint**: clean (0 errors, 0 warnings after `-Wno-MULTITOP`).\\n- **Formal (`bash formal/run_all.sh`)**: **PASS** \\u2014 53 checks passed, 0 failed, on the first attempt.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T05:43:11.786757Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly handles backward branches and JAL, and\\nthe 4-entry RAS covers returns. Forward conditional branches remain predicted\\nnot-taken. A prior 16-entry bimodal attempt produced zero delta, likely because\\npure PC indexing suffered severe aliasing in the small table or because the\\nnew-module integration was not wired correctly. A GShare predictor XORs the PC\\nwith a global history register, reducing aliasing and capturing inter-branch\\ncorrelation that a PC-only table cannot. CoreMark's state-machine and\\nlist-traversal kernels contain correlated forward branches; learning these\\npatterns can eliminate residual mispredict stalls with only ~70 flip-flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry Pattern History Table (2-bit saturating counters) and a 5-bit\\nGlobal History Register (GHR) directly into if_stage.sv. Index the PHT with\\npc[6:2] ^ ghr. For every conditional branch, predict taken when the counter\\nMSB is 1; keep the existing static predictions for JAL, backward branches, and\\nRAS returns untouched. In ex_stage.sv, export the actual branch outcome and\\nPC[6:2] back to IF. On every resolved branch, update the GHR by shifting in\\nthe actual taken bit, and update the indexed PHT counter (increment if taken,\\ndecrement if not, saturating at 0 and 3). Implement everything inline in\\nexisting files to avoid new-module integration risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 5-bit GHR register and 32x2-bit PHT array. Use pc[6:2] ^ ghr to index\\nthe PHT and drive predict_taken for conditional branches (retaining existing\\nstatic rules for JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns). Add feedback\\ninputs from EX stage to update GHR and PHT on resolved branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add bp_update, bp_taken, and bp_pc_idx output ports. Assert bp_update when\\na conditional branch resolves (in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch && !stall).\\nDrive bp_taken from branch_taken and bp_pc_idx from in.pc[6:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the branch predictor feedback signals (bp_update, bp_taken, bp_pc_idx)\\nfrom ex_stage to if_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC+4 in ID stage and pipeline to EX to eliminate redundant adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a pc_plus4 field to id_ex_t (core_pkg.sv). In id_stage.sv latch\\nreg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 alongside the existing ID/EX state. In\\nex_stage.sv replace every occurrence of in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4:\\n(1) alu_result for JAL/JALR, (2) pc_next on misalign trap, (3) redirect_target\\nwhen the branch/jump is not taken. This removes three 32-bit adders from the\\nEX stage at the cost of one adder in ID and 32 extra flip-flops in the ID/EX\\nregister. Because the ID/EX capture path is not the current critical path,\\nthe net effect should be a small Fmax improvement (2-4 MHz) with zero IPC\\nchange.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add logic [31:0] pc_plus4 to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch reg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4 in the JAL/JALR alu_result mux, the misalign pc_next mux, and the redirect_target assignment.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add logic [31:0] pc_plus4 to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch reg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4 in the JAL/JALR alu_result mux, the misalign pc_next mux, and the redirect_target assignment.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:10:42.736477Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline stalls the front-end (PC and combinational IF/ID output) on\\nevery back-end stall: load-use hazards, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. During a\\nload-use bubble or a dmem freeze, the fetch unit sits idle even though the\\ninstruction memory might be ready. A tiny instruction buffer between IF and ID\\nallows the front-end to prefetch instructions while the back-end is stalled,\\nand it can hide single-cycle imem stalls by serving a buffered instruction to\\nID when the bus is not ready. CoreMark spends a noticeable fraction of cycles\\nin load-use bubbles and random memory stalls; decoupling fetch from decode\\nturns many of those dead front-end cycles into productive prefetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer inside if_stage.sv that sits between the raw\\ninstruction fetch and the IF/ID output.  IF pushes a fetched if_id_t bundle\\ninto the buffer whenever imem_ready is high and the buffer is not full.  ID\\npops from the buffer head every cycle the buffer is non-empty.  When the\\nbuffer is empty the output bypasses directly from the current fetch, preserving\\nthe existing combinational path.  Restructure hazard_unit.sv so that stall_if\\nonly asserts when imem_ready is low AND the buffer is full, removing load_use\\nand dmem_stall from the IF stall logic.  ID stall (stall_id) gains a new term\\nthat asserts when the buffer is empty, ensuring ID never decodes a non-existent\\ninstruction.  The buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never\\npollute the queue.  This is a pure structural decoupling: no new modules, just\\ntwo if_id_t registers plus head/tail state in if_stage and updated stall\\nexpressions in hazard_unit.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer for if_id_t bundles.  Implement push on\\nimem_ready && !full, pop when ID consumes, and flush on redirect.\\nDrive the stage output from the buffer head when valid, otherwise\\nbypass the combinational fetch path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Decouple IF stall from back-end stalls.  stall_if asserts only when\\n!imem_ready && buffer_full (or on redirect).  Remove load_use_hazard\\nand dmem_stall from stall_if.  Add buffer_empty to stall_id so ID\\nwaits when no instruction is available.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new buffer_full and buffer_empty signals between if_stage\\nand hazard_unit, and adjust stall/flush connections as needed.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\\nsemantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 311.72, \"delta_pct\": -5.89, \"vs_baseline\": 10.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 132.35, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245804, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10209, \"ff\": 1958, \"seeds\": [132.35, 121.74, 136.56], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:08:40.113110Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r9s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r9s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r9s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r9s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 9}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\n: \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New module adapted from `cores/picorv32/rtl/picorv32.v` module `picorv32_pcpi_div`. Simplified to expose `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `result`, `busy`, `done`. Handles signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 overflow per RV32IM. Keeps the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch from the original.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the case statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0`. Keep the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch completely unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide opcodes and start `div_unit`. Assert a new `div_busy` output while the unit is running. Gate the EX/MEM register update with `!div_busy`; capture `div_unit.result` into `reg_q.alu_result` on the final cycle. Non-divide instructions continue single-cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Combine it with `dmem_stall` so that `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem`, and `hold_mem_wb` are all asserted while `div_busy` is high.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate `div_unit`, wire its control/operand ports to the EX stage, and route the new `div_busy` signal from `ex_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Remove all DIV/REM cocotb tests because the ALU module no longer implements those opcodes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r6s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r6s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r6s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Copy `cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv` verbatim into `cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv`.\\nThe module exposes `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `busy`, `done`, `result` and\\nreferences the global ALU op constants defined in `core_pkg.sv` (which is\\nalready compiled first). Its internal logic is battle-tested and includes\\nthe required `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch.\\n\\nIn `alu.sv`, remove only the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`,\\n`ALU_REMU` cases from the `case (op)` statement so they fall to the\\n`default: out = 32'b0;` path. Leave the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`\\nbranch completely untouched so formal verification continues to see\\ncombinational behaviour for those opcodes.\\n\\nIn `ex_stage.sv`, integrate the divider exactly as v1 does:\\n- Add `is_div_op`, `div_request`, `div_start`, `div_busy`, `div_done`,\\n  `div_result_w`, `div_active_q`, `div_result_valid_q`, `div_result_q`,\\n  `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`, `div_complete`, and\\n  `div_result_selected` signals.\\n- Instantiate `div_unit` with `start=div_start`, `op=in.ctrl.alu_op`,\\n  `a=alu_a`, `b=alu_b`, connecting `busy`, `done`, and `result`.\\n- Set `div_request = in.valid && is_div_op && !in.ctrl.is_illegal &&\\n  !div_active_q`.\\n- Set `div_start = div_request && !stall`.\\n- Set `div_complete = div_active_q && (div_result_valid_q || div_done)`.\\n- Assert a new output `ex_long_busy = div_start || div_busy ||\\n  (div_active_q && !div_complete)`.\\n- In the first EX/MEM always_ff block: on `div_start`, latch `div_active_q`,\\n  save `in`, `rs1`, `rs2` into `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`.\\n  On `div_done && div_active_q`, capture `div_result_w` into\\n  `div_result_q` and set `div_result_valid_q`. On `div_complete && !stall`,\\n  clear `div_active_q` and `div_result_valid_q`.\\n- In the second EX/MEM always_ff block: add `else if (div_complete)` that\\n  writes the saved `div_in_q` state into `reg_q` with `alu_result` set to\\n  `div_result_selected`. Add `else if (div_start || div_active_q)` that\\n  injects a bubble (`reg_q <= '0`). Keep all existing non-divide logic\\n  unchanged.\\n\\nIn `hazard_unit.sv`, add an `ex_long_busy` input and include it in\\n`stall_if` and `stall_id` alongside the existing stall terms. Do NOT add it\\nto `flush_id` \\u2014 we want to hold the divide instruction in ID/EX, not clear\\nit.\\n\\nIn `core.sv`, wire the new `ex_long_busy` output from `ex_stage` to the\\nnew `ex_long_busy` input on `hazard_unit`.\\n\\nIn `test/test_alu.py`, delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/\\nREM/REMU opcodes through the ALU module: `div_signed`, `div_by_zero`,\\n`div_overflow`, `divu`, `divu_by_zero`, `rem_signed`, `rem_by_zero`,\\n`rem_overflow`, `remu`, `remu_by_zero`, and `back_to_back_divides`.\\nThe ALU no longer implements those opcodes, and the proven `div_unit.sv`\\nis verified by cosim and formal instead.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Copy cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv verbatim into this new file. The module is fully proven, includes RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS support, and references the global ALU op constants from core_pkg.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, ALU_REMU cases from the case statement so they fall to default out=32'b0. Keep the ALTOPS branch and all other ALU operations unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate div_unit exactly as cores/v1/rtl/ex_stage.sv does. Add the divider control FSM (is_div_op, div_start, div_active_q, etc.), instantiate div_unit with alu_a/alu_b operands, assert ex_long_busy while dividing, and modify the EX/MEM register logic to capture the saved instruction state on div_complete while emitting bubbles during the divide. Use bench naming (predict_taken, predict_target).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_long_busy input. Include it in stall_if and stall_id alongside the existing stall terms (load_use, imem_stall, dmem_stall). Do not add it to flush_id.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ex_long_busy output from ex_stage to the new ex_long_busy input on hazard_unit. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU opcodes (div_signed, div_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed, rem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides) because the ALU module no longer implements division or remainder.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Copy cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv verbatim into this new file. The module is fully proven, includes RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS support, and references the global ALU op constants from core_pkg.sv.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the non-ALTOPS ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, ALU_REMU cases from the case statement so they fall to default out=32'b0. Keep the ALTOPS branch and all other ALU operations unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate div_unit exactly as cores/v1/rtl/ex_stage.sv does. Add the divider control FSM (is_div_op, div_start, div_active_q, etc.), instantiate div_unit with alu_a/alu_b operands, assert ex_long_busy while dividing, and modify the EX/MEM register logic to capture the saved instruction state on div_complete while emitting bubbles during the divide. Use bench naming (predict_taken, predict_target).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_long_busy input. Include it in stall_if and stall_id alongside the existing stall terms (load_use, imem_stall, dmem_stall). Do not add it to flush_id.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ex_long_busy output from ex_stage to the new ex_long_busy input on hazard_unit. No other top-level changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU opcodes (div_signed, div_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero, rem_signed, rem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero, back_to_back_divides) because the ALU module no longer implements division or remainder.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes \\u2014 Iterative Divider Integration\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- **Added `rtl/div_unit.sv`** \\u2014 copied verbatim from `cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv`. The module implements a 32-cycle shift-subtract divider with full RV32M semantics (signed/unsigned DIV/REM, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow) and includes the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch for formal compatibility.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/alu.sv`** \\u2014 removed the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`, `ALU_REMU` cases from the `case (op)` statement so they fall to `default: out = 32'b0;`. The `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch was left completely untouched, preserving the combinational ALTOPS substitution that formal verification expects.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/ex_stage.sv`** \\u2014 integrated the divider exactly as `cores/v1` does:\\n  - Added `ex_long_busy` output.\\n  - Added divider control signals (`is_div_op`, `div_request`, `div_start`, `div_busy`, `div_done`, `div_result_w`, `div_active_q`, `div_result_valid_q`, `div_result_q`, `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`, `div_complete`, `div_result_selected`).\\n  - Instantiated `div_unit` with operand mux outputs `alu_a` / `alu_b`.\\n  - Split the EX/MEM register logic into two `always_ff` blocks: one for divider state, one for `reg_q`. The `reg_q` block now emits bubbles (`reg_q <= '0`) while a divide is active, and on `div_complete` it writes the saved instruction state with `alu_result` set to the divider result.\\n  - Preserved all existing bench-specific branch/mispredict logic (uses `predict_taken` / `predict_target`, not v1's `predicted_taken` / `predicted_target`).\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/hazard_unit.sv`** \\u2014 added `ex_long_busy` input and included it in `stall_if` and `stall_id` alongside the existing stall terms. `flush_id` was intentionally left unchanged so the divide instruction stays in ID/EX rather than being cleared.\\n\\n- **Modified `rtl/core.sv`** \\u2014 declared `logic ex_long_busy` and wired it from `ex_stage` to `hazard_unit`.\\n\\n- **Modified `test/test_alu.py`** \\u2014 removed all cocotb tests that exercised DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU through the ALU module, plus the now-unused `_check_div` helper and the now-unused opcode imports. The ALU no longer implements those opcodes; divider correctness is covered by cosim and formal.\\n\\n## Deviations from hypothesis\\n\\nNone. The implementation follows the hypothesis verbatim, using bench naming conventions where they differ from v1.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- The divider is 32-cycle iterative. CoreMark contains virtually no integer divisions, so IPC impact is negligible, but a pathological program with back-to-back divides will see a large slowdown.\\n- `div_unit.sv` references global ALU op constants (`ALU_DIV`, etc.) from `core_pkg.sv`. This file is compiled first in all build flows, so the reference is safe.\\n- The `div_in_q` latch saves the entire `id_ex_t` struct. Some fields (e.g., `predict_taken`) are unused when the saved instruction is later written to `reg_q`. Verilator lint is suppressed around `div_in_q` to avoid `UNUSEDSIGNAL` warnings.\\n\\n## Local verification status\\n\\n- **Verilator lint**: clean (0 errors, 0 warnings after `-Wno-MULTITOP`).\\n- **Formal (`bash formal/run_all.sh`)**: **PASS** \\u2014 53 checks passed, 0 failed, on the first attempt.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T05:43:11.786757Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly handles backward branches and JAL, and\\nthe 4-entry RAS covers returns. Forward conditional branches remain predicted\\nnot-taken. A prior 16-entry bimodal attempt produced zero delta, likely because\\npure PC indexing suffered severe aliasing in the small table or because the\\nnew-module integration was not wired correctly. A GShare predictor XORs the PC\\nwith a global history register, reducing aliasing and capturing inter-branch\\ncorrelation that a PC-only table cannot. CoreMark's state-machine and\\nlist-traversal kernels contain correlated forward branches; learning these\\npatterns can eliminate residual mispredict stalls with only ~70 flip-flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry Pattern History Table (2-bit saturating counters) and a 5-bit\\nGlobal History Register (GHR) directly into if_stage.sv. Index the PHT with\\npc[6:2] ^ ghr. For every conditional branch, predict taken when the counter\\nMSB is 1; keep the existing static predictions for JAL, backward branches, and\\nRAS returns untouched. In ex_stage.sv, export the actual branch outcome and\\nPC[6:2] back to IF. On every resolved branch, update the GHR by shifting in\\nthe actual taken bit, and update the indexed PHT counter (increment if taken,\\ndecrement if not, saturating at 0 and 3). Implement everything inline in\\nexisting files to avoid new-module integration risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 5-bit GHR register and 32x2-bit PHT array. Use pc[6:2] ^ ghr to index\\nthe PHT and drive predict_taken for conditional branches (retaining existing\\nstatic rules for JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns). Add feedback\\ninputs from EX stage to update GHR and PHT on resolved branches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add bp_update, bp_taken, and bp_pc_idx output ports. Assert bp_update when\\na conditional branch resolves (in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch && !stall).\\nDrive bp_taken from branch_taken and bp_pc_idx from in.pc[6:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the branch predictor feedback signals (bp_update, bp_taken, bp_pc_idx)\\nfrom ex_stage to if_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC+4 in ID stage and pipeline to EX to eliminate redundant adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a pc_plus4 field to id_ex_t (core_pkg.sv). In id_stage.sv latch\\nreg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 alongside the existing ID/EX state. In\\nex_stage.sv replace every occurrence of in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4:\\n(1) alu_result for JAL/JALR, (2) pc_next on misalign trap, (3) redirect_target\\nwhen the branch/jump is not taken. This removes three 32-bit adders from the\\nEX stage at the cost of one adder in ID and 32 extra flip-flops in the ID/EX\\nregister. Because the ID/EX capture path is not the current critical path,\\nthe net effect should be a small Fmax improvement (2-4 MHz) with zero IPC\\nchange.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add logic [31:0] pc_plus4 to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch reg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4 in the JAL/JALR alu_result mux, the misalign pc_next mux, and the redirect_target assignment.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add logic [31:0] pc_plus4 to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch reg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4 in the JAL/JALR alu_result mux, the misalign pc_next mux, and the redirect_target assignment.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:10:42.736477Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline stalls the front-end (PC and combinational IF/ID output) on\\nevery back-end stall: load-use hazards, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. During a\\nload-use bubble or a dmem freeze, the fetch unit sits idle even though the\\ninstruction memory might be ready. A tiny instruction buffer between IF and ID\\nallows the front-end to prefetch instructions while the back-end is stalled,\\nand it can hide single-cycle imem stalls by serving a buffered instruction to\\nID when the bus is not ready. CoreMark spends a noticeable fraction of cycles\\nin load-use bubbles and random memory stalls; decoupling fetch from decode\\nturns many of those dead front-end cycles into productive prefetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer inside if_stage.sv that sits between the raw\\ninstruction fetch and the IF/ID output.  IF pushes a fetched if_id_t bundle\\ninto the buffer whenever imem_ready is high and the buffer is not full.  ID\\npops from the buffer head every cycle the buffer is non-empty.  When the\\nbuffer is empty the output bypasses directly from the current fetch, preserving\\nthe existing combinational path.  Restructure hazard_unit.sv so that stall_if\\nonly asserts when imem_ready is low AND the buffer is full, removing load_use\\nand dmem_stall from the IF stall logic.  ID stall (stall_id) gains a new term\\nthat asserts when the buffer is empty, ensuring ID never decodes a non-existent\\ninstruction.  The buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never\\npollute the queue.  This is a pure structural decoupling: no new modules, just\\ntwo if_id_t registers plus head/tail state in if_stage and updated stall\\nexpressions in hazard_unit.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer for if_id_t bundles.  Implement push on\\nimem_ready && !full, pop when ID consumes, and flush on redirect.\\nDrive the stage output from the buffer head when valid, otherwise\\nbypass the combinational fetch path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Decouple IF stall from back-end stalls.  stall_if asserts only when\\n!imem_ready && buffer_full (or on redirect).  Remove load_use_hazard\\nand dmem_stall from stall_if.  Add buffer_empty to stall_id so ID\\nwaits when no instruction is available.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new buffer_full and buffer_empty signals between if_stage\\nand hazard_unit, and adjust stall/flush connections as needed.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\\nsemantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 311.72, \"delta_pct\": -5.89, \"vs_baseline\": 10.22, \"fmax_mhz\": 132.35, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245804, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10209, \"ff\": 1958, \"seeds\": [132.35, 121.74, 136.56], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:08:40.113110Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-