{"type":"text","timestamp":1778752779013,"sessionID":"ses_1da23e9c5ffeelLZA5icmOJ2op","part":{"id":"prt_e25ed3a9c001P36cnO1MFUTpdH","messageID":"msg_e25eccc7b001LN612CYImx0T5d","sessionID":"ses_1da23e9c5ffeelLZA5icmOJ2op","type":"text","text":"I've written the structural hypothesis to:\n\n**`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r15s1.yaml`**\n\n### Summary\n\nThe hypothesis proposes moving the pending-store slot **inside** `mem_stage.sv` rather than as a separate top-level module with an external arbiter. \n\n**Why this angle:**\n- A prior store-slot attempt (`hyp-20260514-002-r12s1`) recovered ~33 k CoreMark cycles (~0.8% IPC gain) but regressed Fmax from **140.63 MHz → 128.53 MHz** (–7.89% fitness), likely due to the top-level combinational arbiter on the dmem port path.\n- By keeping the arbitration internal to `mem_stage`, the external dmem port is still driven directly by `mem_stage` combinational outputs—no new top-level combinational delay is introduced—while preserving the same IPC benefit (non-memory instructions can flow through MEM while a buffered store drains on a later cycle when `dmemReady` is high).\n\n**Files changed:**\n- `rtl/mem_stage.sv` — add internal 1-entry store buffer and `mem_wait` export\n- `rtl/hazard_unit.sv` — replace `dmem_ready`/`ex_mem_mem_op` with single `mem_wait` input\n- `rtl/core.sv` — wire `mem_wait` between `mem_stage` and `hazard_unit`\n\n**Expected impact:** +1% fitness (medium confidence), aiming to capture the prior IPC gain without the Fmax penalty.","time":{"start":1778752764572,"end":1778752779012}}}
