& pcpi_div_ready};\n341:\t\t\tENABLE_DIV && pcpi_div_ready: begin\n342:\t\t\t\tpcpi_int_wr = pcpi_div_wr;\n343:\t\t\t\tpcpi_int_rd = pcpi_div_rd;\n2417: * picorv32_pcpi_div\n2420:module picorv32_pcpi_div (\n","exit":0,"description":"Find PicoRV32 divider module","truncated":false},"title":"Find PicoRV32 divider module","time":{"start":1778736250021,"end":1778736250024}},"id":"prt_e24f13a31001ePJJfmJhLy1NSw","sessionID":"ses_1db0f83a4ffehvpEIUlbQzUjKs","messageID":"msg_e24f12cd6002B07wKLDuHONfaG"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778736250533,"sessionID":"ses_1db0f83a4ffehvpEIUlbQzUjKs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"sed -n '1,50p' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | grep -i \"fmax\"","description":"Check baseline Fmax entries"},"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.651702Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multi-cycle iterative divider to break ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths in alu.sv with a compact 32-cycle\\niterative divider (shift-and-subtract / non-restoring) that exposes a start/done\\ninterface. The ex_stage will detect divide ops and hold the EX/MEM register while\\nthe divider runs, asserting a new div_busy signal back to the hazard unit. The\\nhazard unit stalls the entire pipeline upstream (IF, ID, EX) during division,\\nanalogous to a dmem stall. Non-divide ALU ops remain combinational single-cycle.\\nThe ALTOPS formal branch stays unchanged so riscv-formal still sees combinational\\nbehaviour. Removing the massive combinational divider from the ALU output mux should\\nimprove Fmax by ~10 % with <1 % IPC loss, pushing fitness past the 300 target.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with an iterative divider module. Keep all other ALU ops combinational. Preserve ALTOPS branch untouched. Add a start/done interface so EX stage can hold the result across cycles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the iterative divider. Detect divide ops in the ID/EX payload; when active, drive div_busy to the hazard unit and hold the EX/MEM register until done. Capture the divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result on the final cycle. Ensure non-divide instructions flow through in a single cycle as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Assert stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb while div_busy is high, freezing the entire pipeline so the divider can run to completion without losing state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage through hazard_unit and back to the stall network. No other top-level changes required.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with an iterative divider module. Keep all other ALU ops combinational. Preserve ALTOPS branch untouched. Add a start/done interface so EX stage can hold the result across cycles.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the iterative divider. Detect divide ops in the ID/EX payload; when active, drive div_busy to the hazard unit and hold the EX/MEM register until done. Capture the divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result on the final cycle. Ensure non-divide instructions flow through in a single cycle as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a div_busy input. Assert stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb while div_busy is high, freezing the entire pipeline so the divider can run to completion without losing state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage through hazard_unit and back to the stall network. No other top-level changes required.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor to IF stage\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a combinational static predictor in the IF stage with two\\nrules: (1) JAL is always predicted taken, and (2) conditional branches\\nare predicted backward-taken, forward-not-taken (BTFN).  The predictor\\ndecodes the instruction currently on the imem bus, extracts the B-type\\nor J-type immediate, and computes the target address as PC+imm.  When a\\ntaken prediction is made, the IF stage overrides next_pc with the\\ntarget instead of PC+4.  The EX stage recomputes the same prediction\\nfrom the instruction in EX; it asserts redirect only on mispredict\\n(predicted taken but not taken, or vice versa).  This removes the\\nflush penalty for correctly predicted branches and jumps without\\nrequiring any extra pipeline registers or state RAM, keeping LUT usage\\nwithin the remaining budget.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTFN+JAL predictor that computes target from imem_data and overrides next_pc when a taken prediction is made.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Recompute the static prediction in EX and assert redirect only when the actual branch/jump outcome differs from the prediction.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTFN+JAL predictor that computes target from imem_data and overrides next_pc when a taken prediction is made.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Recompute the static prediction in EX and assert redirect only when the actual branch/jump outcome differs from the prediction.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:59:16.575928Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage static predictor: backward branches and JAL always taken\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational prediction logic to if_stage.sv that detects JAL (always\\ntaken) and backward B-type branches (negative offset, i.e. imm[31]=1) in the\\nfetched instruction, computes the target address from the immediate, and\\nsteers next_pc to the target when the target is 4-byte aligned. Extend the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles (core_pkg.sv) with predict_taken and predict_target\\nfields. Modify ex_stage.sv to treat a mismatch between predicted and actual\\noutcome as the redirect condition (mispredict), suppressing the flush on\\ncorrect predictions. This turns the common-case loop back-edge and function\\ncall from a 2-cycle bubble into zero penalty.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 316.95, \"delta_pct\": 12.07, \"vs_baseline\": 12.07, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10559, \"ff\": 1905, \"seeds\": [135.01, 133.96, 138.68], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:51:51.629695Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (improvement, +12.07%): Even a trivial static predictor in IF (backward branches and JAL always taken) removes the common-case flush penalty on loop-heavy code like CoreMark, delivering large IPC wins for near-zero area/Fmax cost.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-stage load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source: the MEM-stage\\nsign/zero-extended load_data (computed combinationally from dmem_rdata and\\nthe byte-offset in ex_mem_w.alu_result). When the instruction currently in\\nMEM is a LOAD and its rd matches the rs1 or rs2 of the instruction in EX,\\nforward the load_data instead of the ALU result. Update forward_unit to\\nencode this as a new select value (e.g. 2'b11). Update ex_stage to mux the\\nnew source into the rs1/rs2 operand paths. Remove the load-use stall term\\nfrom hazard_unit entirely: the dependent instruction now enters EX on the\\ncycle the LOAD enters MEM, and the bypass supplies the correct data\\ncombinationally. The existing dmem_stall freeze (stall_ex_mem) safely covers\\nwait-stated memory: ex_stage recomputes each stalled cycle but only the\\nfinal result is latched when dmem_ready rises, at which point load_data is\\nvalid.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new output port fwd_load_data that exposes the combinationally computed load_data (already derived from dmem_rdata and the byte offset). No other mem_stage logic changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input. In the rs1/rs2 priority chains, when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 && ex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read is true, output the new forwarding code (2'b11) instead of the normal EX/MEM code (2'b01). The new code selects the MEM-stage load_data in the EX operand mux.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes with a fourth option (2'b11 -> fwd_mem_load). Ensure ALU operand selection (alu_a/alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. Keep all other stall logic (imem_stall, dmem_stall, redirect) unchanged. The load-use stall is no longer necessary because MEM-stage forwarding covers the dependency in the same cycle the dependent instruction reaches EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect the ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read signal into forward_unit. No top-level port or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new output port fwd_load_data that exposes the combinationally computed load_data (already derived from dmem_rdata and the byte offset). No other mem_stage logic changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input. In the rs1/rs2 priority chains, when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 && ex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read is true, output the new forwarding code (2'b11) instead of the normal EX/MEM code (2'b01). The new code selects the MEM-stage load_data in the EX operand mux.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes with a fourth option (2'b11 -> fwd_mem_load). Ensure ALU operand selection (alu_a/alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. Keep all other stall logic (imem_stall, dmem_stall, redirect) unchanged. The load-use stall is no longer necessary because MEM-stage forwarding covers the dependency in the same cycle the dependent instruction reaches EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect the ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read signal into forward_unit. No top-level port or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 316.95, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 12.07, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10559, \"ff\": 1905, \"seeds\": [135.01, 133.96, 138.68], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:40:23.552945Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): MEM-to-EX load forwarding from synchronous dmem_rdata creates a long critical path through the operand mux to the ALU that limits Fmax on FPGAs, erasing the theoretical IPC gain from eliminated load-use stalls.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly handles JAL and backward branches,\\nbut all JALR returns are unpredicted (fall-through), causing a 2-cycle\\npipeline flush on every function return. CoreMark contains many function\\ncalls and returns; eliminating these mispredictions should improve IPC\\nwith minimal area/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In IF, detect JALR with rs1=x1\\nand imm=0 as a return; predict taken to RAS top if the stack is non-empty.\\nIn ID, pop the RAS when a predicted return is captured into the ID/EX\\nregister (gated by !flush so wrong-path returns never corrupt the stack).\\nIn ID, detect JAL/JALR writing x1 as a call and push PC+4 to the RAS\\n(also gated by !flush, and safe because wrong-path instructions are\\nflushed before they reach ID). The RAS is purely a performance\\noptimization; mispredictions are still corrected by the existing EX-stage\\nredirect logic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 8-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS ports; detect return-pattern JALR (rs1=x1, imm=0); predict taken to RAS top when stack is non-empty; otherwise fall through.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS push/pop ports; detect call (JAL/JALR writing x1) and push PC+4 on capture into ID/EX; detect return and pop RAS on capture when the return was predicted taken; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire push/pop/addr/top/empty between IF, ID and the new RAS module.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Remove redundant EX-stage adder by reusing IF precomputed branch target\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"In ex_stage.sv, replace all occurrences of (in.pc + in.imm) for branch_target and\\nfor the non-JALR jump_target with the existing in.predict_target field that was\\nprecomputed in IF stage. This removes a 32-bit adder from the branch-resolve and\\nmisalign-check paths in EX. In alu.sv, guard each 64-bit product (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su) so it is computed only when the specific ALU op that consumes it is\\nselected, eliminating unnecessary multiplier switching and helping synthesis\\noptimize the non-M critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use in.predict_target instead of recomputing in.pc+in.imm for branch_target and jump_target (non-JALR cases). This removes a 32-bit adder from the EX critical path for branches and JAL.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate mul_ss, mul_uu, and mul_su computations so each 64-bit product is only active for the specific M-extension multiply op that consumes it (MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU), reducing combinational switching and clarifying the non-M critical path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use in.predict_target instead of recomputing in.pc+in.imm for branch_target and jump_target (non-JALR cases). This removes a 32-bit adder from the EX critical path for branches and JAL.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate mul_ss, mul_uu, and mul_su computations so each 64-bit product is only active for the specific M-extension multiply op that consumes it (MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU), reducing combinational switching and clarifying the non-M critical path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 312.23, \"delta_pct\": -1.49, \"vs_baseline\": 10.4, \"fmax_mhz\": 133.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9877, \"ff\": 1897, \"seeds\": [132.05, 134.95, 133.0], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:14:57.122003Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 3, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -1.49%): Reusing the IF-stage `predict_target` in EX increases combinational fanout on the next-PC critical path and shifts the Fmax bottleneck to fetch, erasing the benefit of the removed EX adder.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 4.5, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:01:44.327280Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (improvement, +4.50%): Function returns (JALR rd=x0, rs1=x1) dominate mispredicts in call-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark; a tiny 4-entry RAS correctly predicts them with minimal area and no impact on EX/MEM timing, yielding pure IPC upside.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\\nalgorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\\nstage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\\ndecodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\\ndiv_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\\nsimplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\\nremoves the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\\nsignificantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"implementation_compile_failed: \", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Instantiating a new `div_unit` submodule without creating its `.sv` source file or adding it to the build manifest causes immediate compile failure; new RTL modules must be created and included before integration.\\n\\n(End of file - total 5 lines)\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry bimodal predictor for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\\nwith PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\\noffset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\\nthe existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\\nstage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\\nincrement if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\\nall counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\\ncurrent static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\\nto the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect\\nthe fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:35:25.447373Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry BTB to remove IF-stage target adder and extend branch coverage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 280.97, \"delta_pct\": -15.17, \"vs_baseline\": -0.65, \"fmax_mhz\": 118.62, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4221744, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 12328, \"ff\": 2983, \"seeds\": [118.62, 121.34, 116.46], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:27:55.029690Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\nto the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 316.95, \"delta_pct\": 12.07, \"vs_baseline\": 12.07, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10559, \"ff\": 1905, \"seeds\": [135.01, 133.96, 138.68], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:51:51.629695Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (improvement, +12.07%): Even a trivial static predictor in IF (backward branches and JAL always taken) removes the common-case flush penalty on loop-heavy code like CoreMark, delivering large IPC wins for near-zero area/Fmax cost.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-stage load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source: the MEM-stage\\nsign/zero-extended load_data (computed combinationally from dmem_rdata and\\nthe byte-offset in ex_mem_w.alu_result). When the instruction currently in\\nMEM is a LOAD and its rd matches the rs1 or rs2 of the instruction in EX,\\nforward the load_data instead of the ALU result. Update forward_unit to\\nencode this as a new select value (e.g. 2'b11). Update ex_stage to mux the\\nnew source into the rs1/rs2 operand paths. Remove the load-use stall term\\nfrom hazard_unit entirely: the dependent instruction now enters EX on the\\ncycle the LOAD enters MEM, and the bypass supplies the correct data\\ncombinationally. The existing dmem_stall freeze (stall_ex_mem) safely covers\\nwait-stated memory: ex_stage recomputes each stalled cycle but only the\\nfinal result is latched when dmem_ready rises, at which point load_data is\\nvalid.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new output port fwd_load_data that exposes the combinationally computed load_data (already derived from dmem_rdata and the byte offset). No other mem_stage logic changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input. In the rs1/rs2 priority chains, when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 && ex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read is true, output the new forwarding code (2'b11) instead of the normal EX/MEM code (2'b01). The new code selects the MEM-stage load_data in the EX operand mux.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes with a fourth option (2'b11 -> fwd_mem_load). Ensure ALU operand selection (alu_a/alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. Keep all other stall logic (imem_stall, dmem_stall, redirect) unchanged. The load-use stall is no longer necessary because MEM-stage forwarding covers the dependency in the same cycle the dependent instruction reaches EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect the ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read signal into forward_unit. No top-level port or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new output port fwd_load_data that exposes the combinationally computed load_data (already derived from dmem_rdata and the byte offset). No other mem_stage logic changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input. In the rs1/rs2 priority chains, when ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd!=0 && ex_mem_rd==id_ex_rs* AND ex_mem_mem_read is true, output the new forwarding code (2'b11) instead of the normal EX/MEM code (2'b01). The new code selects the MEM-stage load_data in the EX operand mux.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load input. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes with a fourth option (2'b11 -> fwd_mem_load). Ensure ALU operand selection (alu_a/alu_b) uses the forwarded values exactly as before.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. Keep all other stall logic (imem_stall, dmem_stall, redirect) unchanged. The load-use stall is no longer necessary because MEM-stage forwarding covers the dependency in the same cycle the dependent instruction reaches EX.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new fwd_load_data output from mem_stage into ex_stage. Connect the ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read signal into forward_unit. No top-level port or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 316.95, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 12.07, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10559, \"ff\": 1905, \"seeds\": [135.01, 133.96, 138.68], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:40:23.552945Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): MEM-to-EX load forwarding from synchronous dmem_rdata creates a long critical path through the operand mux to the ALU that limits Fmax on FPGAs, erasing the theoretical IPC gain from eliminated load-use stalls.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly handles JAL and backward branches,\\nbut all JALR returns are unpredicted (fall-through), causing a 2-cycle\\npipeline flush on every function return. CoreMark contains many function\\ncalls and returns; eliminating these mispredictions should improve IPC\\nwith minimal area/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In IF, detect JALR with rs1=x1\\nand imm=0 as a return; predict taken to RAS top if the stack is non-empty.\\nIn ID, pop the RAS when a predicted return is captured into the ID/EX\\nregister (gated by !flush so wrong-path returns never corrupt the stack).\\nIn ID, detect JAL/JALR writing x1 as a call and push PC+4 to the RAS\\n(also gated by !flush, and safe because wrong-path instructions are\\nflushed before they reach ID). The RAS is purely a performance\\noptimization; mispredictions are still corrected by the existing EX-stage\\nredirect logic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 8-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS ports; detect return-pattern JALR (rs1=x1, imm=0); predict taken to RAS top when stack is non-empty; otherwise fall through.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add RAS push/pop ports; detect call (JAL/JALR writing x1) and push PC+4 on capture into ID/EX; detect return and pop RAS on capture when the return was predicted taken; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire push/pop/addr/top/empty between IF, ID and the new RAS module.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Remove redundant EX-stage adder by reusing IF precomputed branch target\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage already computes branch/JAL targets as predict_target for its static\\npredictor. The EX stage currently recomputes the same pc+imm sum redundantly for\\nbranch resolution, misalign checks, and pc_next selection. This 32-bit adder sits on\\nthe EX-stage critical path alongside the branch comparator, limiting Fmax. Reusing\\nthe precomputed value from the pipeline register removes the adder delay without\\naffecting IPC. Additionally, the ALU eagerly computes all three 64-bit multiplier\\nintermediates on every op; gating them to only the active M-extension multiply op\\nreduces switching and gives the synthesizer a cleaner non-M critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"In ex_stage.sv, replace all occurrences of (in.pc + in.imm) for branch_target and\\nfor the non-JALR jump_target with the existing in.predict_target field that was\\nprecomputed in IF stage. This removes a 32-bit adder from the branch-resolve and\\nmisalign-check paths in EX. In alu.sv, guard each 64-bit product (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su) so it is computed only when the specific ALU op that consumes it is\\nselected, eliminating unnecessary multiplier switching and helping synthesis\\noptimize the non-M critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use in.predict_target instead of recomputing in.pc+in.imm for branch_target and jump_target (non-JALR cases). This removes a 32-bit adder from the EX critical path for branches and JAL.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate mul_ss, mul_uu, and mul_su computations so each 64-bit product is only active for the specific M-extension multiply op that consumes it (MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU), reducing combinational switching and clarifying the non-M critical path.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use in.predict_target instead of recomputing in.pc+in.imm for branch_target and jump_target (non-JALR cases). This removes a 32-bit adder from the EX critical path for branches and JAL.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate mul_ss, mul_uu, and mul_su computations so each 64-bit product is only active for the specific M-extension multiply op that consumes it (MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU), reducing combinational switching and clarifying the non-M critical path.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 312.23, \"delta_pct\": -1.49, \"vs_baseline\": 10.4, \"fmax_mhz\": 133.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9877, \"ff\": 1897, \"seeds\": [132.05, 134.95, 133.0], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:14:57.122003Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 3, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -1.49%): Reusing the IF-stage `predict_target` in EX increases combinational fanout on the next-PC critical path and shifts the Fmax bottleneck to fetch, erasing the benefit of the removed EX adder.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR returns\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 4.5, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:01:44.327280Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (improvement, +4.50%): Function returns (JALR rd=x0, rs1=x1) dominate mispredicts in call-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark; a tiny 4-entry RAS correctly predicts them with minimal area and no impact on EX/MEM timing, yielding pure IPC upside.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\\nalgorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\\nstage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\\ndecodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\\ndiv_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\\nsimplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\\nremoves the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\\nsignificantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder outputs.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and connect any new top-level divider result signals.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"implementation_compile_failed: \", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Instantiating a new `div_unit` submodule without creating its `.sv` source file or adding it to the build manifest causes immediate compile failure; new RTL modules must be created and included before integration.\\n\\n(End of file - total 5 lines)\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry bimodal predictor for forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\\nwith PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\\noffset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\\nthe existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\\nstage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\\nincrement if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\\nall counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\\ncurrent static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\\nto the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect\\nthe fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 331.22, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 17.11, \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10038, \"ff\": 2028, \"seeds\": [125.72, 140.63, 142.37], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:35:25.447373Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"16-entry BTB to remove IF-stage target adder and extend branch coverage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 280.97, \"delta_pct\": -15.17, \"vs_baseline\": -0.65, \"fmax_mhz\": 118.62, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4221744, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\":