{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778736514700,"sessionID":"ses_1db0f83a4ffehvpEIUlbQzUjKs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:15","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r7s1.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r7s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\n2: title: Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\n6:   division using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\n7:   FPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\n8:   critical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\n9:   already above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\n10:   virtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\n11:   cost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\n12: \n13:   Three prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\n14:   failed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\n15:   in this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\n16:   subtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\n17:   integration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\n18:   pipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\n19:   implementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\n20: hypothesis: |\n21:   Copy `cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv` verbatim into `cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv`.\n22:   The module exposes `start`, `op`, `a`, `b`, `busy`, `done`, `result` and\n23:   references the global ALU op constants defined in `core_pkg.sv` (which is\n24:   already compiled first). Its internal logic is battle-tested and includes\n25:   the required `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` branch.\n26: \n27:   In `alu.sv`, remove only the non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV`, `ALU_DIVU`, `ALU_REM`,\n28:   `ALU_REMU` cases from the `case (op)` statement so they fall to the\n29:   `default: out = 32'b0;` path. Leave the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`\n30:   branch completely untouched so formal verification continues to see\n31:   combinational behaviour for those opcodes.\n32: \n33:   In `ex_stage.sv`, integrate the divider exactly as v1 does:\n34:   - Add `is_div_op`, `div_request`, `div_start`, `div_busy`, `div_done`,\n35:     `div_result_w`, `div_active_q`, `div_result_valid_q`, `div_result_q`,\n36:     `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`, `div_complete`, and\n37:     `div_result_selected` signals.\n38:   - Instantiate `div_unit` with `start=div_start`, `op=in.ctrl.alu_op`,\n39:     `a=alu_a`, `b=alu_b`, connecting `busy`, `done`, and `result`.\n40:   - Set `div_request = in.valid && is_div_op && !in.ctrl.is_illegal &&\n41:     !div_active_q`.\n42:   - Set `div_start = div_request && !stall`.\n43:   - Set `div_complete = div_active_q && (div_result_valid_q || div_done)`.\n44:   - Assert a new output `ex_long_busy = div_start || div_busy ||\n45:     (div_active_q && !div_complete)`.\n46:   - In the first EX/MEM always_ff block: on `div_start`, latch `div_active_q`,\n47:     save `in`, `rs1`, `rs2` into `div_in_q`, `div_rs1_q`, `div_rs2_q`.\n48:     On `div_done && div_active_q`, capture `div_result_w` into\n49:     `div_result_q` and set `div_result_valid_q`. On `div_complete && !stall`,\n50:     clear `div_active_q` and `div_result_valid_q`.\n51:   - In the second EX/MEM always_ff block: add `else if (div_complete)` that\n52:     writes the saved `div_in_q` state into `reg_q` with `alu_result` set to\n53:     `div_result_selected`. Add `else if (div_start || div_active_q)` that\n54:     injects a bubble (`reg_q <= '0`). Keep all existing non-divide logic\n55:     unchanged.\n56: \n57:   In `hazard_unit.sv`, add an `ex_long_busy` input and include it in\n58:   `stall_if` and `stall_id` alongside the existing stall terms. Do NOT add it\n59:   to `flush_id` — we want to hold the divide instruction in ID/EX, not clear\n60:   it.\n61: \n62:   In `core.sv`, wire the new `ex_long_busy` output from `ex_stage` to the\n63:   new `ex_long_busy` input on `hazard_unit`.\n64: \n65:   In `test/test_alu.py`, delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/\n66:   REM/REMU opcodes through the ALU module: `div_signed`, `div_by_zero`,\n67:   `div_overflow`, `divu`, `divu_by_zero`, `rem_signed`, `rem_by_zero`,\n68:   `rem_overflow`, `remu`, `remu_by_zero`, and `back_to_back_divides`.\n69:   The ALU no longer implements those opcodes, and the proven `div_unit.sv`\n70:   is verified by cosim and formal instead.\n71: expected_impact:\n72:   fitness_delta_pct: 12\n73:   confidence: high\n74: changes:\n75:   - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n76:     description: >\n77:       Copy cores/v1/rtl/div_unit.sv verbatim into this new file. The module\n78:       is fully proven, includes RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS support, and references\n79:       the global ALU op constants from core_pkg.sv.\n80:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n81:     description: >\n82:       Remove the non-ALTOPS ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, ALU_REMU cases from\n83:       the case statement so they fall to default out=32'b0. Keep the ALTOPS\n84:       branch and all other ALU operations unchanged.\n85:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n86:     description: >\n87:       Integrate div_unit exactly as cores/v1/rtl/ex_stage.sv does. Add the\n88:       divider control FSM (is_div_op, div_start, div_active_q, etc.),\n89:       instantiate div_unit with alu_a/alu_b operands, assert ex_long_busy\n90:       while dividing, and modify the EX/MEM register logic to capture the\n91:       saved instruction state on div_complete while emitting bubbles during\n92:       the divide. Use bench naming (predict_taken, predict_target).\n93:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n94:     description: >\n95:       Add ex_long_busy input. Include it in stall_if and stall_id alongside\n96:       the existing stall terms (load_use, imem_stall, dmem_stall). Do not\n97:       add it to flush_id.\n98:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n99:     description: >\n100:       Wire the new ex_long_busy output from ex_stage to the new ex_long_busy\n101:       input on hazard_unit. No other top-level changes.\n102:   - file: test/test_alu.py\n103:     description: >\n104:       Delete all cocotb tests that exercise DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU opcodes\n105:       (div_signed, div_by_zero, div_overflow, divu, divu_by_zero,\n106:       rem_signed, rem_by_zero, rem_overflow, remu, remu_by_zero,\n107:       back_to_back_divides) because the ALU module no longer implements\n108:       division or remainder.\n\n(End of file - total 108 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\ntitle: Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\n  division using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\n  FPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\n  critical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\n  already above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\n  virtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\n  cost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\n\n  Three prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\n  failed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\n  in this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\n  subtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\n  integration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\n  pipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\n  implementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\nhypothesis: |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778736514686,"end":1778736514699}},"id":"prt_e24f54442001vJyj5WeA5xEH5q","sessionID":"ses_1db0f83a4ffehvpEIUlbQzUjKs","messageID":"msg_e24f534cd001blqOtb8jVM7vtv"}}
