{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778739330227,"sessionID":"ses_1dae05e9affeVdp13bwtw8bOWd","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"functions.grep:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"structural","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"*.jsonl"},"output":"Found 8 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor to IF stage\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a combinational static predictor in the IF stage with two\\nrules: (1) JAL is always predicted taken, and (2) conditional branches\\nare predicted backward-taken, forward-not-taken (BTFN).  The predictor\\ndecodes the instruction currently on the imem bus, extracts the B-type\\nor J-type immediate, and computes the target address as PC+imm.  When a\\ntaken prediction is made, the IF stage overrides next_pc with the\\ntarget instead of PC+4.  The EX stage recomputes the same prediction\\nfrom the instruction in EX; it asserts redirect only on mispredict\\n(predicted taken but not taken, or vice versa).  This removes the\\nflush penalty for correctly predicted branches and jumps without\\nrequiring any extra pipeline registers or state RAM, keeping LUT usage\\nwithin the remaining budget....\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark's matrix and list workloads are heavy with load-to-ALU\\ndependency chains (e.g. lw followed by add/mul). The current 5-stage\\npipeline stalls the entire front-end for one cycle on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM stage\\ncompletes and writes the MEM/WB register. A combinational bypass\\nfrom the MEM-stage load-data extractor to the EX-stage operand muxes\\nallows dependent ALU instructions to execute in the cycle immediately\\nafter the load enters MEM, removing the stall for the common case.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational forwarding path from mem_stage's load_data\\n(post byte-align and sign-extension) to the ex_stage operand muxes.\\nExtend forward_unit to select this source (encoding 2'b11) when the\\ninstruction in EX/MEM is a load and its rd matches the EX-stage rs.\\nModify the hazard_unit to suppress the load-use stall for\\nnon-control-flow instructions: only assert the stall when the\\ninstruction in IF/ID is a branch or JALR, preventing a mispredict\\nredirect from being computed on invalid data during a dmem stall.\\nAll other dependents (ALU, LOAD, STORE) proceed without stalling and\\nconsume the forwarded load data.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data as a new fwd_load_data output port.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input and emit forwarding select 2'b11 when EX/...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260513-001-r3s0', 'hyp-20260513-002-r3s1', 'hyp-20260513-003-r3s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 3}\n\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\\nsynthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\\ncritical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\\nCoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\\nIPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\\napplies to every retired instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\\nalgorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\\nstage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\\ndecodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\\ndiv_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\\nsimplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\\nremoves the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\\nsignificantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 18, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient ...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with inlined iterative multi-cycle FSM\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano\\n20K FPGA these synthesize to a very large pure-LUT network that consumes\\nhundreds of LUT4s and worsens worst-case routing congestion. Current LUT\\nusage is 10038, already above the 10 k target. CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and\\nfreeing area.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths from alu.sv (keep the\\nALTOPS formal branch unchanged). Implement a 32-cycle shift-subtract\\ndivider as a local always_ff FSM directly inside ex_stage.sv\\u2014no new\\nmodule file is required. The FSM converts signed operands to magnitude,\\nperforms unsigned shift-subtract for 32 cycles, then restores the sign\\nfor DIV/REM. When a divide opcode is decoded in EX, ex_stage starts the\\nFSM and asserts div_busy. hazard_unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\\nfreezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the FSM finishes. The result is\\ncaptured into the EX/MEM register on the final cycle. Because the ALU\\nmodule loses its clockless divider, the cocotb ALU unit tests for\\nDIV/REM must be removed.\\n\", \"expected_i...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with proven PicoRV32 iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-tested `picorv32_pcpi_div` module that correctly handles all\\nRV32IM division semantics (signed/unsigned, divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1\\noverflow) and already includes an ALTOPS branch for formal compatibility.\\nAdapting this proven unit eliminates the implementation risk of a hand-written\\nFSM while delivering the same structural benefit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivide/modulo using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA these synthesize to an enormous pure-LUT network that is almost certainly\\nthe worst-case critical path and consumes a large fraction of the LUT budget\\n(current usage is 10038, already above the 10 k target). CoreMark's hot paths\\ncontain essentially no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has\\nnegligible IPC cost while removing the slowest combinational path and freeing\\nsubstantial area.\\n\\nTwo prior attempts to implement a custom iterative divider from scratch failed\\nin cosim due to corner-case bugs. The PicoRV32 core in this same repository\\ncontains a battle-...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with v1-proven iterative unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration t...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline stalls the front-end (PC and combinational IF/ID output) on\\nevery back-end stall: load-use hazards, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. During a\\nload-use bubble or a dmem freeze, the fetch unit sits idle even though the\\ninstruction memory might be ready. A tiny instruction buffer between IF and ID\\nallows the front-end to prefetch instructions while the back-end is stalled,\\nand it can hide single-cycle imem stalls by serving a buffered instruction to\\nID when the bus is not ready. CoreMark spends a noticeable fraction of cycles\\nin load-use bubbles and random memory stalls; decoupling fetch from decode\\nturns many of those dead front-end cycles into productive prefetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer inside if_stage.sv that sits between the raw\\ninstruction fetch and the IF/ID output.  IF pushes a fetched if_id_t bundle\\ninto the buffer whenever imem_ready is high and the buffer is not full.  ID\\npops from the buffer head every cycle the buffer is non-empty.  When the\\nbuffer is empty the output bypasses directly from the current fetch, preserving\\nthe existing combinational path.  Restructure hazard_unit.sv so that stall_if\\nonly asserts when imem_ready is low AND the buffer is full, removing load_use\\nand dmem_stall from the IF stall logic.  ID stall (stall_id) gains a new term\\nthat asserts when the buffer is empty, ensuring ID never decodes a non-existent\\ninstruction.  The buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never\\npollute the queue.  This is a pure structural decoupling: no new modules, just\\ntwo ...","metadata":{"matches":8,"truncated":false},"title":"structural","time":{"start":1778739330206,"end":1778739330226}},"id":"prt_e25203a87001SfLPw9AH9MZKwd","sessionID":"ses_1dae05e9affeVdp13bwtw8bOWd","messageID":"msg_e251fa19f001p6zdwupAHZa2LX"}}
