L once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 5,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 5,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 280.97,\n  \"delta_pct\": -15.17,\n  \"vs_baseline\": -0.65,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 118.62,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4221744,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 12328,\n  \"ff\": 2983,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    118.62,\n    121.34,\n    116.46\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:27:55.029690Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 5,\n  \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\",\n  \"title\": \"8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\\nsemantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 311.72,\n  \"delta_pct\": -5.89,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 10.22,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 132.35,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4245804,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10209,\n  \"ff\": 1958,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    132.35,\n    121.74,\n    136.56\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:08:40.113110Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 8,\n  \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\",\n  \"title\": \"1-entry indirect JALR target cache in IF stage\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Extend if_stage.sv with a 1-entry indirect-JALR target cache\\n(jalr_cache_valid + jalr_cache_target[31:0]).  In the IF-stage prediction\\ncombinational logic, treat any JALR that is not a return (rd=x0 & rs1=x1) as\\ntaken when the cache is valid, steering next_pc to jalr_cache_target.  When\\nthe cache is invalid the fetch falls through to pc+4 as before.  In\\nex_stage.sv, when a non-return JALR resolves and the instruction is not\\nasserting redirect itself, drive the actual jump_target back to IF as an\\nupdate value; if_stage latches it into the cache register on the next clock\\nedge.  The existing EX-stage mispredict logic naturally corrects a stale\\ncache entry.  Wire the two new update signals (jalr_cache_update and\\njalr_cache_update_target) between ex_stage and if_stage through core.sv.\\nNo other pipeline stages are touched, keeping the change localized to the\\nfront-end prediction path.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_valid and jalr_cache_target flops; extend predict_taken/predict_target to select cached target for non-return JALR; add update input ports.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target output ports; assert update on resolved non-return JALR when not redirecting.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Wire the new jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_valid and jalr_cache_target flops; extend predict_taken/predict_target to select cached target for non-return JALR; add update input ports.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target output ports; assert update on resolved non-return JALR when not redirecting.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Wire the new jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 331.22,\n  \"delta_pct\": 0.0,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 17.11,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 140.63,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4245805,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10038,\n  \"ff\": 2028,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    125.72,\n    140.63,\n    142.37\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:40:22.954154Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 9\n}\n","exit":0,"description":"Get details of prior predictor regressions","truncated":false},"title":"Get details of prior predictor regressions","time":{"start":1778741015892,"end":1778741015896}},"id":"prt_e2539e6d7001GLKXoHxPR57rY6","sessionID":"ses_1dac77996ffe0i2FM86AbKPGLm","messageID":"msg_e25392cf20023U0gmu48dJ25ji"}}
