{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778743426612,"sessionID":"ses_1daa88ea5ffeH5QJYa7MtuowY0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -o '\"category\": \"predictor\".*\"outcome\": \"[^\"]*\"' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | sort -t'\"' -k14,14","description":"List all predictor outcomes"},"output":"\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational prediction logic to if_stage.sv that detects JAL (always\\ntaken) and backward B-type branches (negative offset, i.e. imm[31]=1) in the\\nfetched instruction, computes the target address from the immediate, and\\nsteers next_pc to the target when the target is 4-byte aligned. Extend the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles (core_pkg.sv) with predict_taken and predict_target\\nfields. Modify ex_stage.sv to treat a mismatch between predicted and actual\\noutcome as the redirect condition (mispredict), suppressing the flush on\\ncorrect predictions. This turns the common-case loop back-edge and function\\ncall from a 2-cycle bubble into zero penalty.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\\nsemantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparison functions via a function-pointer (JALR x1, rs1, 0).  Both are hot\\nand mispredict every time.  A 1-entry untagged cache that remembers the last\\nresolved target of a non-return JALR introduces only 33 flip-flops and a\\ntrivial combinational mux in the IF stage, adding near-zero delay to the\\nfetch critical path while eliminating most of these mispredicts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend if_stage.sv with a 1-entry indirect-JALR target cache\\n(jalr_cache_valid + jalr_cache_target[31:0]).  In the IF-stage prediction\\ncombinational logic, treat any JALR that is not a return (rd=x0 & rs1=x1) as\\ntaken when the cache is valid, steering next_pc to jalr_cache_target.  When\\nthe cache is invalid the fetch falls through to pc+4 as before.  In\\nex_stage.sv, when a non-return JALR resolves and the instruction is not\\nasserting redirect itself, drive the actual jump_target back to IF as an\\nupdate value; if_stage latches it into the cache register on the next clock\\nedge.  The existing EX-stage mispredict logic naturally corrects a stale\\ncache entry.  Wire the two new update signals (jalr_cache_update and\\njalr_cache_update_target) between ex_stage and if_stage through core.sv.\\nNo other pipeline stages are touched, keeping the change localized to the\\nfront-end prediction path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_valid and jalr_cache_target flops; extend predict_taken/predict_target to select cached target for non-return JALR; add update input ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target output ports; assert update on resolved non-return JALR when not redirecting.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_valid and jalr_cache_target flops; extend predict_taken/predict_target to select cached target for non-return JALR; add update input ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target output ports; assert update on resolved non-return JALR when not redirecting.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new jalr_cache_update and jalr_cache_update_target signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\\ntaken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\\npredicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\\nand state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\\n2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\\nmany of these stalls for negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\\nwith PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\\noffset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\\nthe existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\\nstage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\\nincrement if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\\nall counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\\ncurrent static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\\nto the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect\\nthe fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\", \"description\": \"New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters. Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep their existing behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor table learns from execution history.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF-stage next-PC path is the current Fmax bottleneck. It contains a full\\n32-bit adder that recomputes branch/JAL targets (pc+imm) even though the EX\\nstage already has an identical adder for resolution. This redundancy lengthens\\nthe critical path without adding value. A small Branch Target Buffer (BTB)\\ncaches resolved targets and is read combinationally from the PC, letting the\\nIF stage choose next_pc from the BTB or a lightweight pc+4 incrementer.\\nRemoving the slow pc+imm adder from fetch shortens the critical path and\\nshould raise Fmax. As a side benefit the BTB naturally covers forward taken\\nbranches and JAL once they have been seen, improving IPC for cases the static\\npredictor misses.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 16-entry direct-mapped BTB (valid + tag + target) indexed by PC[5:2].\\nIn if_stage.sv replace the combinational JAL/branch target adders with a BTB\\nlookup: on tag hit next_pc receives the cached target, on miss the fetch falls\\nthrough to pc+4. The RAS return check is preserved with priority over the BTB.\\nThe existing id_ex_t.predict_taken and predict_target fields are driven from\\nthe BTB/RAS so EX-stage mispredict detection continues to work unchanged.\\nIn ex_stage.sv, when a branch or JAL resolves taken the PC and actual_target\\nare written into the BTB; when a branch resolves not-taken the matching BTB\\nentry is invalidated. JALR instructions are never written to the BTB so the\\nRAS remains the sole return predictor. The IF-stage pc+imm adder is removed\\nentirely, shrinking the fetch critical path while the EX-stage adder continues\\nto handle resolution and misalign checks.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New 16-entry direct-mapped BTB with combinational read (PC[5:2] -> hit/target) and synchronous update port (write index, tag, target, valid).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove JAL and branch target adders; read BTB with pc; mux next_pc from RAS top (returns), BTB target (hit), or pc+4 (miss); drive predict_taken/predict_target into the IF/ID bundle from these sources.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add BTB update outputs; on resolved taken branch/JAL drive a BTB write with the EX-stage PC and actual_target; on not-taken branch drive a BTB clear for the matching index/tag. Do not update BTB for JALR.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB module and wire its read ports to IF and update ports to EX.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\"\n","metadata":{"output":"\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational prediction logic to if_stage.sv that detects JAL (always\\ntaken) and backward B-type branches (negative offset, i.e. imm[31]=1) in the\\nfetched instruction, computes the target address from the immediate, and\\nsteers next_pc to the target when the target is 4-byte aligned. Extend the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles (core_pkg.sv) with predict_taken and predict_target\\nfields. Modify ex_stage.sv to treat a mismatch between predicted and actual\\noutcome as the redirect condition (mispredict), suppressing the flush on\\ncorrect predictions. This turns the common-case loop back-edge and function\\ncall from a 2-cycle bubble into zero penalty.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target when appropriate. Pass prediction metadata through the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture predict_taken and predict_target from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional redirect-on-taken with mispredict detection: compare actual branch/jump outcome and target against the prediction fields from ID/EX. Only assert redirect when they disagree.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current static predictor correctly predicts JAL and backward branches,\\nbut every function return (JALR reading x1, writing x0) is predicted\\nnot-taken, incurring a 2-cycle pipeline flush. CoreMark contains frequent\\nfunction calls and returns. A small Return Address Stack predicts return\\naddresses with very high accuracy for minimal area cost, directly\\nimproving IPC without touching the critical EX or MEM paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry Return Address Stack (RAS). In the IF stage, detect\\nreturn-pattern JALR instructions (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1); when the\\nRAS is non-empty, predict taken and steer next_pc to the RAS top entry.\\nIn the ID stage, detect calls (JAL or JALR writing x1) and push PC+4\\nonto the RAS; detect returns and pop the RAS. RAS updates are gated by\\n!flush so wrong-path instructions never corrupt the stack. EX-stage\\nredirect logic continues to verify predictions and correct mispredicts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"New 4-entry Return Address Stack module with push/pop/top/empty ports.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect return-pattern JALR; when RAS is non-empty assert predict_taken and use ras_top as predict_target.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect calls (JAL/JALR writing x1) to push PC+4; detect returns to pop RAS; gate both on !flush.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate RAS and wire top/empty to IF stage, push/pop/addr to ID stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\\nsemantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ras.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\\nshift-register entry array with a fixed 8\\u00d732-bit array plus a 3-bit\\nstack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\\nsp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\\ncombinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\\npush-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\\nwithout incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\\nso core.sv needs no protocol changes.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\\nras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\\n(opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\\nremain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\\nras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\\n(JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\\nwith gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\\npush/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\\nports or protocol changes are needed.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\"\n\"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing predictor correctly handles JAL, backward conditional branches,\\nand RAS-predicted returns.  Every indirect jump and indirect function call\\n(non-return JALR) is currently predicted not-taken, causing a 2-cycle pipeline\\nflush on each execution.  CoreMark's state-machine kernel compiles its dense\\nswitch statement to a jump table (JALR x0, rs1, 0), and the list kernel calls\\ncomparis