{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778747182830,"sessionID":"ses_1da682b06ffenZMz5sHSWkRx4V","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (improvement, +12.07%): Even a trivial static predictor in IF (backward branches and JAL always taken) removes the common-case flush penalty on loop-heavy code like CoreMark, delivering large IPC wins for near-zero area/Fmax cost.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): MEM-to-EX load forwarding from synchronous dmem_rdata creates a long critical path through the operand mux to the ALU that limits Fmax on FPGAs, erasing the theoretical IPC gain from eliminated load-use stalls.\n3: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -1.49%): Reusing the IF-stage `predict_target` in EX increases combinational fanout on the next-PC critical path and shifts the Fmax bottleneck to fetch, erasing the benefit of the removed EX adder.\n4: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (improvement, +4.50%): Function returns (JALR rd=x0, rs1=x1) dominate mispredicts in call-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark; a tiny 4-entry RAS correctly predicts them with minimal area and no impact on EX/MEM timing, yielding pure IPC upside.\n5: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Instantiating a new `div_unit` submodule without creating its `.sv` source file or adding it to the build manifest causes immediate compile failure; new RTL modules must be created and included before integration.\n6: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r10s0 (regression, +0.00%): Restricting MEM-to-EX forwarding to raw LW words only still yields zero fitness improvement, indicating the dmem_rdata→operand mux→ALU combinational path remains Fmax-critical on FPGA even without byte/halfword extraction logic.\n7: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r11s1 (regression, +0.00%): A 1-entry IF skid buffer cannot improve IPC when the benchmark is back-end bound by EX/MEM-stage hazards and multi-cycle dmem stalls; front-end decoupling only creates slack that the stalled back-end cannot absorb.\n8: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r12s2 (regression, -1.97%): A 32-entry 1-bit BHT defaulting to not-taken regressed CoreMark because sporadic taken forward branches poison their entry, causing repeated mispredicts on subsequent not-taken instances until the bit flips back — worse than the static fall-through baseline.\n\n(End of file - total 8 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (improvement, +12.07%): Even a trivial static predictor in IF (backward branches and JAL always taken) removes the common-case flush penalty on loop-heavy code like CoreMark, delivering large IPC wins for near-zero area/Fmax cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): MEM-to-EX load forwarding from synchronous dmem_rdata creates a long critical path through the operand mux to the ALU that limits Fmax on FPGAs, erasing the theoretical IPC gain from eliminated load-use stalls.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -1.49%): Reusing the IF-stage `predict_target` in EX increases combinational fanout on the next-PC critical path and shifts the Fmax bottleneck to fetch, erasing the benefit of the removed EX adder.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (improvement, +4.50%): Function returns (JALR rd=x0, rs1=x1) dominate mispredicts in call-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark; a tiny 4-entry RAS correctly predicts them with minimal area and no impact on EX/MEM timing, yielding pure IPC upside.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Instantiating a new `div_unit` submodule without creating its `.sv` source file or adding it to the build manifest causes immediate compile failure; new RTL modules must be created and included before integration.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r10s0 (regression, +0.00%): Restricting MEM-to-EX forwarding to raw LW words only still yields zero fitness improvement, indicating the dmem_rdata→operand mux→ALU combinational path remains Fmax-critical on FPGA even without byte/halfword extraction logic.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r11s1 (regression, +0.00%): A 1-entry IF skid buffer cannot improve IPC when the benchmark is back-end bound by EX/MEM-stage hazards and multi-cycle dmem stalls; front-end decoupling only creates slack that the stalled back-end cannot absorb.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r12s2 (regression, -1.97%): A 32-entry 1-bit BHT defaulting to not-taken regressed CoreMark because sporadic taken forward branches poison their entry, causing repeated mispredicts on subsequent not-taken instances until the bit flips back — worse than the static fall-through baseline.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778747182811,"end":1778747182828}},"id":"prt_e25980c290015zrrB5ELXQ2fAq","sessionID":"ses_1da682b06ffenZMz5sHSWkRx4V","messageID":"msg_e2597d534001CLypsY4r5OjDMz"}}
