{"type":"text","timestamp":1778749768548,"sessionID":"ses_1da4a0cf5ffeV48EjI4AvaVgTV","part":{"id":"prt_e25bf5e74001BaIiLQM0ie01Pi","messageID":"msg_e25bf297f002ZA5PSOP4Ncas2B","sessionID":"ses_1da4a0cf5ffeV48EjI4AvaVgTV","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r14s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** A 4-entry direct-mapped BTB for non-return JALR targets. The current core predicts returns via RAS and always-taken for JAL/backward branches, but leaves indirect calls and jump-table dispatches as guaranteed not-taken mispredicts. The BTB caches the resolved target on the first execution of a JALR, eliminating the flush penalty on every repeat from the same PC—particularly valuable for CoreMark's repeated `cmp` function-pointer calls in `core_list_find`. It falls back to existing behaviour on miss, so there is no regression risk for unseen or one-off JALRs.","time":{"start":1778749759092,"end":1778749768546}}}
