{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778729157335,"sessionID":"ses_1db818b37ffeZJFm5ZwDscudKR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r4s1.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r4s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\n2: title: Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\n6:   divide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\n7:   synthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\n8:   critical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\n9:   CoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\n10:   IPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\n11:   applies to every retired instruction.\n12: hypothesis: |\n13:   Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\n14:   algorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\n15:   stage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\n16:   decodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\n17:   div_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\n18:   freezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\n19:   simplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\n20:   removes the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax\n21:   significantly for near-zero IPC cost on CoreMark.\n22: expected_impact:\n23:   fitness_delta_pct: 18\n24:   confidence: medium\n25: changes:\n26:   - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n27:     description: >\n28:       New 32-cycle iterative divider using shift-and-subtract with\n29:       separate sign/magnitude paths for signed DIV/REM and unsigned\n30:       DIVU/REMU. Exposes start, busy, done, quotient and remainder\n31:       outputs.\n32:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n33:     description: >\n34:       Remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and the associated\n35:       division/modulo operators so the ALU critical path shrinks to\n36:       the remaining arithmetic/logic operations.\n37:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n38:     description: >\n39:       Instantiate div_unit alongside the ALU. Detect DIV/REM opcodes\n40:       and start the divider. While busy, capture and hold the divide\n41:       result. Output a div_busy flag to the hazard unit.\n42:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n43:     description: >\n44:       Add div_busy input and include it in the stall_if, stall_id,\n45:       and stall_ex_mem combinational logic so the entire pipeline\n46:       freezes during a multi-cycle divide.\n47:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n48:     description: >\n49:       Wire the new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit and\n50:       connect any new top-level divider result signals.\n\n(End of file - total 50 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\ntitle: Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The ALU currently implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\n  divide/modulo using SystemVerilog / and % operators. On FPGA these\n  synthesize to enormous combinational networks that create the longest\n  critical-path delay and consume a large fraction of LUT budget.\n  CoreMark's hot paths contain essentially no integer divisions, so the\n  IPC cost of a multi-cycle divider is negligible while the Fmax gain\n  applies to every retired instruction.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a dedicated 32-cycle iterative divider module (shift-subtract\n  algorithm with sign/magnitude handling) and integrate it into the EX\n  stage. The divider exposes start, busy, and result ports. When EX\n  decodes a DIV/REM opcode it starts the divider and asserts a new\n  div_busy signal. The hazard unit treats div_busy like dmem_stall,\n  freezing IF, ID, and EX/MEM until the divider completes. The ALU is\n  simplified to remove combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths. This\n  removes the slowest combinational path from the design, raising Fmax","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r4s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778729157323,"end":1778729157334}},"id":"prt_e2484fd210014RMZrULuxZ0hJ6","sessionID":"ses_1db818b37ffeZJFm5ZwDscudKR","messageID":"msg_e2484db4200147P2muukZIyBfR"}}
