{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778729199296,"sessionID":"ses_1db818b37ffeZJFm5ZwDscudKR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r4s2.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r4s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\n2: title: 16-entry bimodal predictor for forward branches\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\n6:   taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\n7:   predicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\n8:   and state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\n9:   2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\n10:   many of these stalls for negligible area cost.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\n13:   with PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\n14:   offset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\n15:   the existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\n16:   stage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\n17:   increment if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\n18:   all counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\n19:   current static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\n20:   to the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect\n21:   the fetch critical path.\n22: expected_impact:\n23:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n24:   confidence: medium\n25: changes:\n26:   - file: rtl/bimodal_pred.sv\n27:     description: >\n28:       New module holding a 16-entry array of 2-bit saturating counters.\n29:       Exposes a read port (pc -> predict_taken) for the IF stage and an\n30:       update port (pc, taken) for the EX stage. Counters initialize to\n31:       weakly-not-taken and saturate at 0 and 3.\n32:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n33:     description: >\n34:       Add predictor read ports. For conditional branches that are not\n35:       backward, use the bimodal predictor output instead of hard-wiring\n36:       predict_taken to 0. JAL, backward branches, and RAS returns keep\n37:       their existing behavior.\n38:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n39:     description: >\n40:       Add predictor update output ports. When a conditional branch\n41:       resolves, drive update_en, update_pc (the branch PC), and\n42:       update_taken (the actual branch direction) so the predictor\n43:       table learns from execution history.\n44:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n45:     description: >\n46:       Instantiate the bimodal predictor module and wire its read port\n47:       to if_stage and its update port to ex_stage.\n\n(End of file - total 47 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\ntitle: 16-entry bimodal predictor for forward branches\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The existing predictor covers backward branches (always taken), JAL (always\n  taken), and returns (4-entry RAS). Forward conditional branches are always\n  predicted not-taken. CoreMark contains forward branches in linked-list search\n  and state-machine control flow that are taken frequently, each incurring a\n  2-cycle mispredict penalty. A tiny learned direction predictor can eliminate\n  many of these stalls for negligible area cost.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 16-entry 2-bit saturating counter bimodal predictor. Index the table\n  with PC[5:2]. For forward conditional branches (B-type with non-negative\n  offset) predict taken when the counter's MSB is 1 (states 10 or 11). Keep\n  the existing static backward-taken and RAS predictions unchanged. In the EX\n  stage, when a conditional branch resolves, update the indexed counter:\n  increment if taken, decrement if not taken, saturating at 0 and 3. Initialize\n  all counters to 2'b01 (weakly not taken) so the default behavior matches the\n  current static predictor. This adds only 32 flip-flops and a small read mux\n  to the IF stage, with the update path entirely in EX where it cannot affect","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r4s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778729199288,"end":1778729199295}},"id":"prt_e24859f560020K0ZuxU64uxtIR","sessionID":"ses_1db818b37ffeZJFm5ZwDscudKR","messageID":"msg_e24858eb2001WEwEdTTsCEZRts"}}
