{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778738194071,"sessionID":"ses_1daf826e4ffe02tFs8OBi8OPvf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r8s2.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r8s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\n2: title: 8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\n6:   predicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\n7:   chains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\n8:   which exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\n9:   every deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\n10:   Replacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\n11:   removes the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\n12:   area and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\n13:   regression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\n14: hypothesis: |\n15:   Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\n16:   The circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\n17:   entries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\n18:   This allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\n19:   call stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\n20:   adding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\n21:   Update if_stage and id_stage to use the new RAS ports (top/empty/push/pop\n22:   semantics stay identical, so wiring changes inside core.sv are trivial).\n23: expected_impact:\n24:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n25:   confidence: medium\n26: changes:\n27:   - file: rtl/ras.sv\n28:     description: |\n29:       Rewrite the RAS module as an 8-entry circular buffer. Replace the\n30:       shift-register entry array with a fixed 8×32-bit array plus a 3-bit\n31:       stack pointer and 4-bit count. Push writes to entry[sp] and increments\n32:       sp (wrapping modulo 8); pop decrements sp. The top entry is read\n33:       combinationally as entry[(sp-1) mod 8]. Empty when count==0. On\n34:       push-when-full, overwrite the oldest entry (bottom) by advancing sp\n35:       without incrementing count. Keep the same push/pop/top/empty interface\n36:       so core.sv needs no protocol changes.\n37:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n38:     description: |\n39:       No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_top,\n40:       ras_empty) is unchanged. Verify that return-pattern JALR detection\n41:       (opcode=JALR, rd=x0, rs1=x1) and its priority over other predictions\n42:       remain intact.\n43:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n44:     description: |\n45:       No functional change required because the RAS interface (ras_push,\n46:       ras_pop, ras_push_addr) is unchanged. Verify that call detection\n47:       (JAL/JALR writing x1) and return detection (JALR reading x1, writing x0)\n48:       with gating on !flush and !stall remain intact.\n49:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n50:     description: |\n51:       Instantiate the rewritten ras module with DEPTH=8. Wire the same\n52:       push/pop/addr/top/empty signals between IF, ID, and RAS; no new\n53:       ports or protocol changes are needed.\n\n(End of file - total 53 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\ntitle: 8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\n  predicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\n  chains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\n  which exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\n  every deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\n  Replacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\n  removes the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\n  area and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\n  regression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\n  The circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\n  entries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\n  This allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\n  call stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\n  adding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r8s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778738194060,"end":1778738194070}},"id":"prt_e250ee378001Soq15trkerQz2e","sessionID":"ses_1daf826e4ffe02tFs8OBi8OPvf","messageID":"msg_e250ed060001dBAuw6xuZHtNzD"}}
