{"type":"text","timestamp":1778738205361,"sessionID":"ses_1daf826e4ffe02tFs8OBi8OPvf","part":{"id":"prt_e250f05d7001eWvFdQF8FQN8KI","messageID":"msg_e250eea1e001vlXlMpQKsZgH4n","sessionID":"ses_1daf826e4ffe02tFs8OBi8OPvf","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis file written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r8s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** The hypothesis proposes replacing the proven-but-shallow 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS. The circular-buffer design eliminates costly per-push/pop shift logic, making deeper coverage affordable. This targets return-address mispredicts on CoreMark's recursive `core_list_mergesort` call stacks, which can exceed the current 4-entry capacity. The interface remains unchanged, so integration risk is low and the critical IF-stage path is untouched.","time":{"start":1778738202071,"end":1778738205358}}}
