formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration that correctly handles divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 overflow, and\\npipeline stalling. Reusing that proven implementation eliminates the\\nimplementation risk that broke the earlier attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as combinational 32-bit\\ndivision using SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. On the Tang Nano 20K\\nFPGA this synthesizes to a massive pure-LUT network that dominates the\\ncritical path and consumes hundreds of LUT4s. Current LUT usage is 10038,\\nalready above the 10000 target, and Fmax is 140.63 MHz. CoreMark contains\\nvirtually no integer divisions, so a multi-cycle divider has negligible IPC\\ncost while shortening the critical path and freeing area.\\n\\nThree prior attempts to write a custom iterative divider from scratch all\\nfailed in cosim due to corner-case bugs. However, the `cores/v1` directory\\nin this same repository contains a fully proven `div_unit.sv` (shift-\\nsubtract, 32-cycle, with ALTOPS formal support) plus a working EX-stage\\nintegration t... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/div_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly handles backward branches and JAL, and\\nthe 4-entry RAS covers returns. Forward conditional branches remain predicted\\nnot-taken. A prior 16-entry bimodal attempt produced zero delta, likely because\\npure PC indexing suffered severe aliasing in the small table or because the\\nnew-module integration was not wired correctly. A GShare predictor XORs the PC\\nwith a global history register, reducing aliasing and capturing inter-branch\\ncorrelation that a PC-only table cannot. CoreMark's state-machine and\\nlist-traversal kernels contain correlated forward branches; learning these\\npatterns can eliminate residual mispredict stalls with only ~70 flip-flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry Pattern History Table (2-bit saturating counters) and a 5-bit\\nGlobal History Register (GHR) directly into if_stage.sv. Index the PHT with\\npc[6:2] ^ ghr. For every conditional branch, predict taken when the counter\\nMSB is 1; keep the existing static predictions for JAL, backward branches, and\\nRAS returns untouched. In ex_stage.sv, export the actual branch outcome and\\nPC[6:2] back to IF. On every resolved branch, update the GHR by shifting in\\nthe actual taken bit, and update the indexed PHT counter (increment if taken,\\ndecrement if not, saturating at 0 and 3). Implement everything inline in\\nexisting files to avoid new-module integration risk.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 5-bit GHR register and 32x2-bit PHT array. Use pc[6:2] ^ ghr to index\\nthe PHT and drive predict_... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC+4 in ID stage and pipeline to EX to eliminate redundant adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage recomputes pc+4 in three separate places: JAL/JALR return-address\\n(alu_result), misaligned-trap fallback (pc_next), and not-taken mispredict\\nredirect_target. Each recomputation is a 32-bit adder on paths that are known\\nto be timing-sensitive (redirect goes from EX back to IF). By computing pc+4\\nonce in the ID stage and carrying it through the id_ex_t pipeline register,\\nEX replaces those adders with a register read, shortening the mispredict\\nrecovery path and the EX/MEM write-data setup path without affecting IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a pc_plus4 field to id_ex_t (core_pkg.sv). In id_stage.sv latch\\nreg_q.pc_plus4 <= in.pc + 32'd4 alongside the existing ID/EX state. In\\nex_stage.sv replace every occurrence of in.pc + 32'd4 with in.pc_plus4:\\n(1) alu_result for JAL/JALR, (2) pc_next on misalign trap, (3) redirect_target\\nwhen the branch/jump is not taken. This removes three 32-bit adders from the\\nEX stage at the cost of one adder in ID and 32 extra flip-flops in the ID/EX\\nregister. Because the ID/EX capture path is not the current critical path,\\nthe net effect should be a small Fmax improvement (2-4 MHz) with zero IPC\\nchange.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/co... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline stalls the front-end (PC and combinational IF/ID output) on\\nevery back-end stall: load-use hazards, dmem stalls, and imem stalls. During a\\nload-use bubble or a dmem freeze, the fetch unit sits idle even though the\\ninstruction memory might be ready. A tiny instruction buffer between IF and ID\\nallows the front-end to prefetch instructions while the back-end is stalled,\\nand it can hide single-cycle imem stalls by serving a buffered instruction to\\nID when the bus is not ready. CoreMark spends a noticeable fraction of cycles\\nin load-use bubbles and random memory stalls; decoupling fetch from decode\\nturns many of those dead front-end cycles into productive prefetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2-entry FIFO buffer inside if_stage.sv that sits between the raw\\ninstruction fetch and the IF/ID output.  IF pushes a fetched if_id_t bundle\\ninto the buffer whenever imem_ready is high and the buffer is not full.  ID\\npops from the buffer head every cycle the buffer is non-empty.  When the\\nbuffer is empty the output bypasses directly from the current fetch, preserving\\nthe existing combinational path.  Restructure hazard_unit.sv so that stall_if\\nonly asserts when imem_ready is low AND the buffer is full, removing load_use\\nand dmem_stall from the IF stall logic.  ID stall (stall_id) gains a new term\\nthat asserts when the buffer is empty, ensuring ID never decodes a non-existent\\ninstruction.  The buffer is flushed on redirect so wrong-path instructions never\\npollute the queue.  This is a pure structural decoupling: no new modules, just\\ntwo ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"8-entry circular-buffer RAS to cut recursive-call mispredicts\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 4-entry shift-register RAS already gives a +4.5% fitness boost by\\npredicting function returns, but its shallow depth overflows on recursive call\\nchains. CoreMark's linked-list kernel uses recursive mergesort (depth ~5-7),\\nwhich exceeds the 4-entry capacity and causes return-address mispredicts on\\nevery deep recursive path. A deeper RAS directly eliminates these stalls.\\nReplacing the shift-register implementation with a circular-buffer design\\nremoves the costly per-push/pop shift logic, making 8 entries affordable in\\narea and keeping the top/empty read path fast enough to avoid the Fmax\\nregression that destroyed the prior BTB attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 4-entry shift-register RAS with an 8-entry circular-buffer RAS.\\nThe circular buffer uses a top pointer and count instead of shifting all\\nentries on every push or pop, eliminating combinational shift-mux overhead.\\nThis allows doubling the depth for minimal area increase, catching deeper\\ncall stacks such as CoreMark's recursive list-traversal functions without\\nadding new modules or touching the critical IF-stage target-addition path.\\nUpdate if_stage and i... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 25 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.651702Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Multi-cycle iterative divider to break ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench core's ALU implements all M-extension ops combinationally, including 32-bit\\nsigned/unsigned division and remainder. On the Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-LV18) FPGA,\\ncombinational division synthesizes to a very large pure-LUT network that dominates\\nstatic-timing critical path. The current Fmax is 127 MHz; meeting the 135 MHz target\\nrequires shortening the longest combinational path. CoreMark uses division minimally\\n(matrix operations are MUL-heavy, not DIV-heavy), so a multi-cycle divider will have\\nnegligible IPC impact while removing the slow path and raising Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU paths in alu.sv with a compact 32-cycle\\niterative divider (shift-and-subtract / non-restoring) that exposes a start/done\\ninterface. The ex_stage will detect divide ops and hold the EX/MEM register while\\nthe divider runs, asserting a new div_busy signal back to the hazard unit. The\\nhazard unit stalls the entire pipeline upstream (IF, ID, EX) during division,\\nanalogous to a dmem stall. Non-divide ALU ops remain combinational single-cycle.\\nThe ALTOPS formal branch stays unchanged so riscv-formal still sees combinational\\nbehaviour. Removing the massive combinational divider from the ALU output ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor to IF stage\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core incurs a one-cycle bubble on every taken branch and\\nunconditional jump because the next-PC is only resolved in EX.  CoreMark\\nspends a significant fraction of cycles in tight loops (backward branches)\\nand function calls (JAL), so eliminating these bubbles will raise IPC.\\nMoving the next-PC selection into IF also replaces the long critical\\npath that currently runs from ID/EX through EX-stage branch resolution\\nback to the PC register with a short local path, offering a small Fmax\\ngain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Introduce a combinational static predictor in the IF stage with two\\nrules: (1) JAL is always predicted taken, and (2) conditional branches\\nare predicted backward-taken, forward-not-taken (BTFN).  The predictor\\ndecodes the instruction currently on the imem bus, extracts the B-type\\nor J-type immediate, and computes the target address as PC+imm.  When a\\ntaken prediction is made, the IF stage overrides next_pc with the\\ntarget instead of PC+4.  The EX stage recomputes the same prediction\\nfrom the instruction in EX; it asserts redirect only on mispredict\\n(predicted taken but not taken, or vice versa).  This removes the\\nflush penalty for correctly predicted branches and jumps without\\nrequiring any extra pipeline registers or state RAM, keeping LUT usage\\nwithin the remaining budget.... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"IF-stage static predictor: backward branches and JAL always taken\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline core resolves all control flow in EX, incurring a 2-cycle flush\\npenalty for every taken branch and jump. CoreMark is loop-heavy; loop\\nback-edges are almost always backward branches, and function calls use JAL.\\nPredicting these in IF eliminates the flush penalty for the common case,\\nimproving IPC with minimal additional logic and low Fmax risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational prediction logic to if_stage.sv that detects JAL (always\\ntaken) and backward B-type branches (negative offset, i.e. imm[31]=1) in the\\nfetched instruction, computes the target address from the immediate, and\\nsteers next_pc to the target when the target is 4-byte aligned. Extend the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles (core_pkg.sv) with predict_taken and predict_target\\nfields. Modify ex_stage.sv to treat a mismatch between predicted and actual\\noutcome as the redirect condition (mispredict), suppressing the flush on\\ncorrect predictions. This turns the common-case loop back-edge and function\\ncall from a 2-cycle bubble into zero penalty.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predict_taken and predict_target fields to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational decode of JAL and backward B-type in fetched instruction, compute target address from immediate, and mux next_pc to the predicted target ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-stage load forwarding to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The baseline 5-stage pipeline inserts a one-cycle bubble on every load-use\\nhazard because the loaded data is not available until the MEM/WB register.\\nCoreMark's list traversal and state-machine kernels contain many back-to-back\\nload-then-ALU and load-then-store patterns. Each bubble costs ~0.7-1.0 % of\\ntotal execution cycles. A combinational bypass from the MEM-stage load-data\\nmux directly to the EX-stage operand muxes removes the stall entirely for\\nall forwarding-compatible dependencies, improving IPC at near-zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the forwarding network with a third source: the MEM-stage\\nsign/zero-extended load_data (computed combinationally from dmem_rdata and\\nthe byte-offset in ex_mem_w.alu_result). When the instruction currently in\\nMEM is a LOAD and its rd matches the