{"type":"text","timestamp":1778739952352,"sessionID":"ses_1dae05f62ffeBgOtDtJWADHW20","part":{"id":"prt_e2529a8b4001CYVqtVgtB9k68Y","messageID":"msg_e25299596001U9rgvC72R9Xorf","sessionID":"ses_1dae05f62ffeBgOtDtJWADHW20","type":"text","text":"I wrote the hypothesis file to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r9s2.yaml`\n\nThe hypothesis proposes adding a **1-entry indirect-JALR target cache** in the IF stage. It targets the remaining class of unpredictable control-flow instructions—non-return JALRs (indirect jumps and indirect function calls)—which currently incur a 2-cycle mispredict penalty. Because the read path is just a flop output muxed into the existing next-PC logic, the combinational delay added to the fetch stage is minimal, while the cache can eliminate many of the frequent mispredicts in CoreMark's state-machine and list kernels.","time":{"start":1778739947700,"end":1778739952349}}}
